# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ancient-philosophy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The work is largely an elaboration of the stories of martyrdom in the book 2 Maccabees: that of the woman with seven sons and the scribe Eleazar, who are tortured to death by Seleucid King Antiochus IV Epiphanes in an attempt to make them renounce their adherence to Judaism.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] What 2 Maccabees covered in one chapter and a half, 4 Maccabees extends to a full 14 chapters of dialogue and philosophical discussion.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] 4 Maccabees recasts the story as one of reason and logic: the martyrs will be rewarded in the afterlife, so it is rational to continue to obey Jewish law, even at the risk of torture and death.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The work consists of a prologue and two main sections.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The last chapters concern the author's impressions drawn from these martyrdoms.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] It has been suggested that, while 2 Maccabees was written with appeals to emotion, sentiment, and drama (*pathos*), 4 Maccabees is considerably more intellectual about the matter.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The martyred woman calmly debates her captors, explaining why her actions are rational given God's promise of rewards in the afterlife, using arguments akin to those favored by Stoic philosophy.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The author of 4 Maccabees still appreciates the power of arousing emotions, however.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The work goes into more grisly detail concerning the martyrdoms themselves than 2 Maccabees; "even now, we ourselves shudder as we hear of the suffering of these young men" (4 Maccabees 14:9).
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The author has the clear rhetorical intent of arousing admiration and emulation of these examples of devotion to the Jewish law.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The work is in fluent and complicated Greek using the rhetorical argumentative style of the time.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Harry Orlinsky describes it as "an elaborate variation, in philosophical and highly dramatic vein, of the theme" of 2 Maccabees 6:18–7:4.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The work uses secular allusions to Greek-style athletics and military contests, calling Eleazar a "noble athlete" and the martyred mother of the seven sons a "soldier of God".
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The work defends the merits of Judaism in a Hellenized world.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] According to it, devout practice of Judaism perfects the values held dear in Greek and Roman contexts, with the martyrs presented in terms reminiscent of Greek sages.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The book is ascribed to the Jewish historian Josephus by Eusebius and Jerome, and this opinion was accepted for many years, leading to its inclusion in many editions of Josephus' works.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Later scholars have rejected this claim of authorship, however.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] There are differences of language and style; 4 Maccabees makes several historical errors that Josephus's work does not make; and the ideology of the two seems to conflict (Josephus favored accommodation toward Gentile practices, not the uncompromising stance seen in 4 Maccabees).
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The author was probably not from Roman Judea, as the book includes a minor geographical mistake about the layout of Jerusalem, Judea was largely Aramaic-speaking in the era, and the tone of the work suggests the defense of a cultural minority in a Hellenistic environment.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] As such, he was probably a diaspora Jew, although from where is unclear.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Alexandria was the largest site of literary Greek Jewish works in the era, but scholars such as Hans Freudenthal and Eduard Norden think that the religious outlook of the book does not easily match Alexandrian Jewish thought.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The original title of the work, if any, is uncertain.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The Septuagint is what gave it its modern name of "4 Maccabees" to distinguish it from the other books of Maccabees in it, but it almost certainly was not the original title of the work.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Eusebius and Jerome wrote that the work of Josephus on the martyrdoms of the Maccabees – presumably 4 Maccabees – was called "On the Sovereignty of Reason", suggesting that might have been the original title.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] This title would be consistent with the conventions of Greek philosophical and ethical works of the period (e.g., Seneca's "On Anger", "On Benefits", "On the Constancy of the Wise Person").
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The book is generally dated between 20 and 130 CE.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Bickerman suggests a composition date somewhere between 20–54 CE; Moses Hadas agrees with that range and further suggests that perhaps around 40 CE during the reign of Roman Emperor Caligula would fit.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Other scholars such as André Dupont-Sommer support a later date, perhaps during the reign of Emperor Hadrian (118–135 CE).
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The last chapter differs from the earlier chapters in style, and is a somewhat disorganized summary of what has been stated before.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] According to some scholars, this might be evidence that the last chapter is a later addition to the work, though this is disputed.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The argument in favor of it being an original part of the composition is that the book would have a weak ending without the final chapter, and that the style and vocabulary of the final chapter is not as different as claimed.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The change of direction with chapter 17 supports the view of the work as a homily held before a Greek-speaking audience on the feast of Hanukkah, as advanced by Ewald and Freudenthal, where this would be a rhetorical element to draw the listeners into the discourse.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Others hold that a homily would have to be based on scriptural texts, which this work is only loosely.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] In terms of genre, the book resembles both the panegyric or encomium (speeches in honor of a particular person or subject) as well as the philosophical diatribe.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The work has a clearly Stoic stamp as the thesis it seeks to demonstrate is that "pious reason exercises mastery over the emotions" (4 Maccabees 1:1).
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The work also resonates with sentiments articulated by other philosophical schools such as Platonism.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The writer believes in the immortality of the soul, but never mentions the resurrection of the dead.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Good souls are said to live forever in happiness with the patriarchs and God, but even the evil souls are held to be immortal.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The suffering and martyrdom of the Maccabees is seen by the author to be vicarious for the Jewish nation, and the author portrays martyrdom in general as bringing atonement for the past sins of the Jews.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] In this it is similar to the Testament of Moses, which was written or updated around the same time period, and similarly praises the virtues of martyrdom and resistance.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] While the setting of the book is during the Seleucid and Maccabee period of Judea, it is generally believed that the author intended to apply the lessons from this era in his current time.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The book thus functions as an endorsement of fidelity to Jewish customs and law and against assimilation to Gentile practice where this conflicted with the Torah.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] David A. deSilva considers the work's depiction of personal trust and faithfulness toward God as being in line with early Christian theology; notably, he argues that the Jewish Christian Epistle to the Hebrews has a similar viewpoint on the matter of the meaning of faith.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The work also seems to have proto-Christian views on the nature of atonement: that the sacrifice of animals at the Temple (impossible in the Maccabean era, as well as for diaspora Jews in the author's era) could be replaced by a sacrifice of "obedience unto death" by faithful humans.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] While it is difficult to know for sure, deSilva also hypothesizes that the kind of promotion of the value of the Jewish Law for shaping an ethical life might have been used by the Jewish Christians who sought to persuade Gentile Christians also to adopt a Jewish way of life.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] These Jewish Christians, however, have not left a written legacy of their own; we have access to their arguments only as reflected in Paul's letters angrily denouncing their understanding of Christianity.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] 4 Maccabees enjoyed little influence on later Judaism.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Hellenistic Judaism waned with time, and the book was not translated to Hebrew in its era.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] It was not included in the Masoretic canon of Hebrew scriptures, the Tanakh, and thus was not considered canonical by later Jews.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Stories of the martyrs did circulate among Jews in rabbinic literature, but likely from independent traditions rather than 4 Maccabees directly.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The work was preserved largely among Christians.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] These early Christians both were interested in stories of martyrdom and generally admired Stoicism.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The book seems to have been reasonably esteemed in the early Christian church: sermons and works of John Chrysostom, Gregory of Nazianzus, and Ambrose evince familiarity with 4 Maccabees.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The work also had a profound impact on Origen.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The popular Martyrdom of Polycarp exhibits many similarities with the stories in 4 Maccabees.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Despite circulating among early Christian communities who used versions of the Septuagint that included 4 Maccabees, church councils were generally more skeptical.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] In Greek lists, the book appears in the Apostolic Canons, but no others.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] In Latin lists, it appears in Codex Claromontanus.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] If the Gelasian Decree is taken as an accurate record of the "Damasine canon" compiled by Pope Damasus I (366–383 CE), then neither 3 Maccabees nor 4 Maccabees was in the Western, Latin church's list of canonical books of the 4th century.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The book was not translated by Jerome into the Latin Vulgate.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] As a result, the work was generally obscure in Latin-reading Western Europe.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] In the Greek-reading East, it seems the work was more popular, but still failed to be included in later canon lists.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The Eastern Orthodox Canon was laid out in the Quinisext Council in Trullo (692 CE).
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The Trullo list included the first three books of Maccabees, but did not include 4 Maccabees as canonical.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] It is no longer printed in Romanian Bibles today.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The Syriac, Coptic, and Ethiopic language Oriental Orthodox Churches do not include the book as canonical either.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Some ancient manuscripts of the Syriac Orthodox church include the work, but this trend eventually stopped.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] 4 Maccabees is in two of the three of the most ancient manuscripts of the Septuagint: the Codex Sinaiticus (4th century) and the Codex Alexandrinus (5th century).
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] It is not, however, in the Codex Vaticanus.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] With the exception of the section 5:12-12:1, it is found also in the eight or ninth-century Codex Venetus.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] There are over 70 extant Greek manuscripts of 4 Maccabees.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Four pre-modern translations of 4 Maccabees are known.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] There survives a complete Syriac translation, as well as a Latin adaptation under the title *Passio Sanctorum Machabaeorum* (Suffering of the Holy Maccabees).
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] One of the Syriac versions was titled *The Fourth Book of the Maccabees and Their Mother*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The Latin text was made around the same time as Ambrose's *De Jacob et vita beata* (388), which includes an independent partial translation of 4 Maccabees.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The *Passio* was probably completed before the appearance of the Vulgate Bible in 405–406 and was probably produced in Gaul.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Fragments of an abridged Sahidic Coptic translation were discovered by Enzo Lucchesi in the 1980s.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] They have been edited and translated into English.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Maximus the Greek produced an abridged Slavonic translation.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The Fourth Book of Maccabees is not in the Vulgate and so is absent from the Apocrypha of the Roman Bible as well as from Protestant Bibles.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] Erasmus published at Cologne in 1517, expanded in 1524, a very free Latin paraphrase of 4 Maccabees, possibly based on the *Passio*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] After the invention of the printing press, 4 Maccabees was first mass printed in a 1526 edition of the Septuagint made in Strasbourg, albeit one based on a less reliable manuscript with a number of printer's errors.
[src:ancient-philosophy/4-maccabees] The work is included in the Revised Standard Version (RSV), the New Revised Standard Version (NRSV), and New Revised Standard Version Updated Edition (NRSVUE).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] "about the dharma") refers to a class of Buddhist texts, the first of which date from the 3rd century BCE.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Abhidharma texts contain detailed scholastic presentations of Buddhist doctrine, including doctrines that appear in canonical Buddhist scriptures and commentaries.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] "Abhidharma" also refers to the scholastic method itself, and the knowledge (prajña) that this method is said to study and cultivate.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] There are different types of Abhidharma literature.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The early canonical Abhidharma works, such as the Pali *Abhidhamma Piṭaka*, are not philosophical treatises but mainly summaries and expositions of early Buddhist doctrinal lists with their accompanying explanations.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] These texts developed out of early Buddhist lists or matrices (*mātṛkās*) of key teachings.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Later post-canonical Abhidharma works were written as either large treatises (*śāstra*), as commentaries (*aṭṭhakathā*), or as smaller introductory manuals.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] There were numerous schools of Abhidharma in India, such as the Theravada, and the Vaibhāṣika.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] They are more developed philosophical works which include many innovations and doctrines not found in the canonical Abhidharma.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Abhidharma remains an important field of scholarship among the Theravāda, Mahāyāna, and Vajrayāna schools of Buddhism.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] They held that Abhidharma was taught by the Buddha to his most eminent disciples, and that therefore this justified the inclusion of Abhidharma texts into their scriptural canon.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] According to Collett Cox, Abhidharma started as a systematic elaboration of the teachings of the Buddhist sūtras, but later developed independent doctrines.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Two interpretations of the term "Abhi-dharma" are common.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] According to Analayo, the initial meaning of Abhidharma in the earliest texts (such as the *Mahāgosiṅga-sutta* and its parallels) was simply a discussion concerning the Dharma, or talking about the Dharma.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] In this sense, *abhi* has the meaning of "about" or "concerning," and can also be seen in the parallel term *abhivinaya* (which just means discussions about the vinaya).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The other interpretation, where *abhi* is interpreted as meaning "higher" or "superior", and thus *Abhidharma* means "higher teaching", seems to have been a later development.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Some Western scholars have considered the Abhidharma to be the core of what is referred to as "Buddhism and psychology".
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Other scholars on the topic, such as Nyanaponika Thera and Dan Lusthaus, describe Abhidharma as a Buddhist phenomenology while Noa Ronkin and Kenneth Inada equate it with process philosophy.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Bhikkhu Bodhi writes that the system of the *Abhidhamma Piṭaka* is "simultaneously a philosophy, a psychology and an ethics, all integrated into the framework of a program for liberation." According to L.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Cousins, the Buddhist sūtras deal with sequences and processes, while the Abhidharma texts describe occasions and events.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Modern scholars generally believe that the canonical Abhidharma texts emerged after the time of Gautama Buddha, in around the 3rd century BCE.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Therefore, the canonical Abhidharma works are generally claimed by scholars not to represent the words of the Buddha himself, but those of later Buddhist thinkers.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Peter Skilling describes the Abhidharma literature as "the end-product of several centuries of intellectual endeavor".
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Vinaya accounts on the compilation of the Buddhist Canon following the *parinirvāṇa* of Gautama Buddha (c.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] 5th century BCE) offer various and sometimes conflicting narratives regarding the canonical status of Abhidharma.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] According to Analayo, "the Mūlasarvāstivāda Vinaya does not explicitly mention the Abhidharma, although it reports that on this occasion Mahākāśyapa recited the mātṛkā(s)." Analayo thinks that this reflects an early stage, when what later became Abhidharma was called the *mātṛkās*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The term appears in some sūtras, such as the *Mahāgopālaka-sutta* (and its Sanskrit parallel) which says that a learned monk is one who knows the Dharma, Vinaya, and the mātṛkās.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Western scholars of Buddhist studies such as André Migot, Edward J.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Thomas, Erich Frauwallner, Rupert Gethin, and Johannes Bronkhorst have argued that the Abhidharma was based on early and ancient lists of doctrinal terms which are called *mātikās* (Sanskrit: *mātṛkā*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Migot points to the mention of a "*Mātṛkā Piṭaka"* in the *Cullavagga* as the precursor to the canonical *Abhidharma*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Migot argues that this *Mātṛkā Piṭaka*, said to have been recited by Mahākāśyapa at the First Council according to the *Ashokavadana*, likely began as a condensed version of the Buddhist doctrine that was expanded over time.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Thomas and Frauwallner both argue that while the Abhidharma texts of the different schools were compiled separately and have major differences, they are based on an "ancient core" of common material.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Rupert Gethin also writes that the *mātikās* are from an earlier date than the Abhidharma texts themselves.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The extensive use of *mātṛkā* can be found in some early Buddhist texts, including the *Saṅgīti Sutta* and *Dasuttara Sutta* of the Dīgha Nikāya, as well as the *Saṅgīti Sūtra* and *Daśottara Sūtra* of the Dīrgha Āgama.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Similar lists of numerically arranged doctrinal terms can be found in AN 10.27 and AN 10.28.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Tse fu Kuan also argues that certain sūtras of the *Aṅguttara Nikāya* (AN 3.25, AN 4.87–90, AN 9.42–51) illustrates an Abhidharma method.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Another text which contains a similar list that acts as a doctrinal summary is the *Madhyama-āgama* ("Discourse on Explaining the Spheres", MĀ 86) which includes a list of thirty one topics to be taught to newly ordained monastics.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The last sutra of the *Madhyama-āgama* (MĀ 222) contains a similar doctrinal summary listing, which combines three lists into one: a list of eight activities, a list of ten mental qualities and practices, and the twelve links of dependent arising.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] These two do not have any parallels in Pali.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] According to Analayo, another important doctrinal list which appears in the early texts is the "thirty seven qualities that are conducive to awakening" (*bodhipākṣikā dharmāḥ*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This *mātṛkā* appears in various sūtras, like the *Pāsādika-sutta*, the *Sāmagāma-sutta* (and their parallels), and in the *Mahāparinirvāṇa-sūtra*, where it is said to have been taught by the Buddha just before passing away.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Analayo notes that these various lists served a useful purpose in early Buddhism since they served as aids for the memorization and teaching of the Buddhist doctrine.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The use of lists containing doctrinal statements can similarly be seen in Jain literature.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The fact that these lists were seen by the early Buddhists as a way to preserve and memorize the doctrine can be seen in the *Saṅgīti Sūtra* and its various parallels, which mention how the Jain community became divided over doctrinal matters after the death of their leader.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The sutta depicts Śāriputra as reciting a list of doctrinal terms and stating that the community will remain "united, unanimous, and in unison we will not dispute" regarding the teaching and also states they will recite together the doctrine.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The close connection between the *Saṅgīti Sūtra* and Abhidharma can be seen in the fact that it became the basis for one of the seven canonical Abhidharma texts belonging to the Sarvāstivāda school, the *Saṅgītiparyāya*, which is effectively a commentary on the sūtra.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Frauwallner notes that basic fundamental concepts such as the 12 *āyatanāni,* the 18 *dhatāvah*, and the 5 *skandhāh* often occur as a group in the early Buddhist texts.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] He also points out another such list that occurs in various texts "comprises several groups of elements of import for entanglement in the cycle of existence" and was modeled on the *Oghavagga* of the *Samyuttanikaya*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Another related early method is called the *mātṛkā* ("attribute"), and refers to lists of terms divided by a dyad or triad of attributes.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] For example, terms could be grouped into those things that are *rūpa* (form, physical) or *arūpa* (formless), *saṃskṛtam* (constructed) or *asaṃskṛtam,* and the triad of *kuśalam* (wholesome), *akuśalam* (unwholesome), or *avyākṛtam* (indetermined).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] An early form of this method can be found in the *Dasuttara Sutta*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The explanations of the various elements in these lists also dealt with how these elements were connected (*saṃprayoga*) with each other.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Over time, the need arose for an overarching way to classify all these terms and doctrinal elements, and the first such framework was to subsume or include (*saṃgraha*) all main terms into the schema of the 12 *āyatanāni,* the 18 *dhatāvah*, and the 5 *skandhāh*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Over time, the initial scholastic method of listing and categorizing terms was expanded in order to provide a complete and comprehensive systematization of the Buddhist doctrine.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] According to Analayo, these various lists were also not presented alone, but included some kind of commentary and explanation which was also part of the oral tradition.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Sometimes this commentary included quotations from other sutras, and traces of this can be found in the canonical Abhidharma texts.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] As time passed, these commentaries and their accompanying lists became inseparable from each other, and the commentaries gained canonical status.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Therefore, the different Buddhist Abhidharma texts were developed over time as Buddhist monks and philosophers expanded their analytical methods in different ways.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Since this happened in different monastic communities located in different regions, they developed in separate doctrinal directions.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This divergence was perhaps enhanced by the various schisms in the early Buddhist community and also by geographic distance.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] According to Frauwallner, the period of the development of the canonical Abhidharma texts is between 250 and 50 BCE.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] By the time, the different canons began to be written down, and as a result the Abhidharma texts of the early Buddhist schools were substantially different, as can be seen in how different the canonical Abhidharma texts are in the Sarvāstivādin and Theravādin schools.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] These differences are much more pronounced than among the other canonical collections (Sūtras, Āgama, and Vinaya).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] As such, the Abhidharma collections of the various Buddhist schools are much more unique to each sect.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The various Abhidharmic traditions grew to have very fundamental philosophical disagreements with each other (such as on the status of the person, or temporal eternalism).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Thus, according to Frauwallner, the different Abhidharma canons contained collections of doctrines which were sometimes unrelated to each other and sometimes contradictory.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] These different Abhidharmic theories were (together with differences in Vinaya) some of the various causes for the splits in the monastic Saṃgha, which resulted in the fragmented early Buddhist landscape of the early Buddhist schools.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] These various Abhidharma works were not accepted by all Indian Buddhist schools as canonical; for example, the Mahāsāṃghika school seems not to have accepted them as part of their Buddhist canon.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Another school included most of the *Khuddaka Nikāya* within the *Abhidhamma Piṭaka*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] After the closing of the foundational Buddhist canons, Abhidharma texts continued to be composed, but now they were either commentaries on the canonical texts (like the Pāli *Aṭṭhakathās* and the *Mahāvibhāṣa*), or independent treatises (*śāstra*) in their own right.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] In these post-canonical texts, further doctrinal developments and innovations can be found.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Some of these texts surpassed the canonical Abhidharma in influence and popularity, becoming the orthodox summas of their particular schools' Abhidharma.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Two exegetical texts, both from the 5th century, stand above the rest as the most influential.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The works of Buddhaghosa (5th century CE), particularly the *Visuddhimagga*, remains the main reference work of the Theravāda school, while the *Abhidharmakośa* (4–5th century CE) of Vasubandhu remains the primary source for Abhidharma studies in both Indo-Tibetan Buddhism and East Asian Buddhism.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] In the modern era, only the Abhidharma texts of the Sarvāstivādins and the Theravādins have survived as complete collections, each consisting of seven books with accompanying commentarial literature.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] A small number of other Abhidharma texts are preserved in the Chinese Canon and also in Sanskrit fragments, such as the *Śāriputra Abhidharma Śāstra* of the Dharmaguptaka school and various texts from the Pudgalavāda tradition.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] These different traditions have some similarities, suggesting either interaction between groups or some common ground antedating the separation of the schools.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] In the Theravāda tradition it was held that the Abhidhamma was not a later addition, but rather was taught in the fourth week of Gautama Buddha's enlightenment.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Theravada tradition is unique in regarding its Abhidharma as having been taught in its complete form by the Buddha as a single teaching, with the exception of the Kathavatthu, which contains material relating to later disputes and was held to only have been presented as an outline.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] According to their tradition, devas built a beautiful jeweled residence for the Buddha to the north-east of the Bodhi tree, where he meditated and delivered the Abhidharma teachings to gathered deities in the Trāyastriṃśa heaven, including his deceased mother Māyā.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The tradition holds that the Buddha gave daily summaries of the teachings given in the heavenly realm to the bhikkhu Sariputta, who passed them on.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvāstivāda-Vaibhāṣika held that the Buddha and his disciples taught the Abhidharma, but that it was scattered throughout the canon.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Only after his death was the Abhidharma compiled systematically by his elder disciples and was recited by Ananda at the first Buddhist council.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Sautrāntika school ('those who rely on the sutras') rejected the status of the Abhidharma as being Buddhavacana (word of the Buddha), they held it was the work of different monks after his death, and that this was the reason different Abhidharma schools varied widely in their doctrines.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] However, this school still studied and debated on Abhidharma concepts and thus did not seek to question the method of the Abhidharma in its entirety.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Indeed, there were numerous Abhidharma texts written from an Abhidharma perspective.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Abhidharma texts' field of inquiry extends to the entire Buddhadharma, since their goal was to outline, systematize and analyze all of the teachings.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Abhidharmic thought also extends beyond the sutras to cover new philosophical and psychological ground which is only implicit in sutras or not present at all.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] There are certain doctrines which were developed or even invented by the Abhidharmikas and these became grounds for the debates among the different early Buddhist schools.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The "base upon which the entire [Abhidhamma] system rests" is the 'dhamma theory' and this theory 'penetrated all the early schools'.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] For the Abhidharmikas, the ultimate components of existence, the elementary constituents of experience were called *dhammas* (Pali: *dhammas*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This concept has been variously translated as "factors" (Collett Cox), "psychic characteristics" (Bronkhorst), "phenomena" (Nyanaponika) and "psycho-physical events" (Ronkin).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The early Buddhist scriptures give various lists of the constituents of the person such as the five skandhas, the six or 18 dhatus, and the twelve sense bases.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] In Abhidhamma literature, these lists of dhammas systematically arranged and they were seen as the ultimate entities or momentary events which make up the fabric of people's experience of reality.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The idea was to create an exhaustive list of all possible phenomena that make up the world.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The conventional reality of substantial objects and persons is merely a conceptual construct imputed by the mind on a flux of dhammas.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] However, dhammas are never seen as individually separate entities, but are always dependently conditioned by other dhammas in a stream of momentary constellations of dhammas, constantly coming into being and vanishing, always in flux.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Perception and thinking is then seen as a combination of various dhammas.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Cittas (awareness events) are never experienced on their own, but are always intentional and hence accompanied by various mental factors (cetasikas), in a constantly flowing stream of experience occurrences.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Human experience is thus explained by a series of dynamic processes and their patterns of relationships with each other.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Buddhist Abhidhamma philosophers then sought to explain all experience by creating lists and matrices (matikas) of these dhammas, which varied by school.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This dhamma is unconditioned it neither arises nor ceases due to causal interaction.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvastivada Abhidharma also used these, along with a fifth category: "factors dissociated from thought" (*cittaviprayuktasaṃskāra*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvastivadas also included three dharmas in the fourth "unconditioned" category instead of just one, the dharma of space and two states of cessation.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Abhidharma project was thus to provide a completely exhaustive account of every possible type of conscious experience in terms of its constituent factors and their relations.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Theravada tradition holds that there were 82 types of possible dhammas – 82 types of occurrences in the experiential world, while the general Sarvastivada tradition eventually enumerated 75 dharma types.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] For the Abhidharmikas, truth was twofold and there are two ways of looking at reality.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] One way is the way of everyday experience and of normal worldly persons.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This is the category of the nominal and the conceptual (paññatti), and is termed the conventional truth (saṃvṛti-satya).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] However, the way of the Abhidharma, and hence the way of enlightened persons like the Buddha, who have developed the true insight (vipassana), sees reality as the constant stream of collections of dharmas, and this way of seeing the world is ultimate truth (paramārtha-satya).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] As the Indian Buddhist Vasubandhu writes: "Anything the idea of which does not occur upon division or upon mental analysis, such as an object like a pot, that is a 'conceptual fiction'.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The ultimately real is otherwise." For Vasubandhu then, something is not the ultimately real if it 'disappears under analysis', but is merely conventional.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The ultimate goal of the Abhidharma is Nirvana and hence the Abhidharmikas systematized dhammas into those which are skillful (kusala), purify the mind and lead to liberation, and those which are unskillful and do not.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Abhidharma then has a soteriological purpose, first and foremost and its goal is to support Buddhist practice and meditation.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Abhidharmikas often used the term svabhāva (Pali: sabhāva) to explain the causal workings of dharmas.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This term was used in different ways by the different Buddhist schools.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This term does not appear in the sutras.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The examination of these characteristics was held to be extremely important, the Sarvastivada Mahavibhasa states "Abhidharma is [precisely] the analysis of the svalaksana and samanya-laksana of dharmas".
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] According to Peter Harvey, the Theravadin view of dharmas was that "'They are dhammas because they uphold their own nature [sabhaava].
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] They are dhammas because they are upheld by conditions or they are upheld according to their own nature' (Asl.39).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The *Visuddhimagga* of Buddhaghosa, the most influential classical Theravada treatise, states that not-self does not become apparent because it is concealed by "compactness" when one does not give attention to the various elements which make up the person.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvastivadins saw dharmas as the ultimately 'real entities' (sad-dravya), though they also held that dharmas were dependently originated.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] For the Sarvastivadins, a synonym for svabhava is avayaya (a 'part'), the smallest possible unit which cannot be analyzed into smaller parts and hence it is ultimately real as opposed to only conventionally real (such as a chariot or a person).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] However, the Sarvastivadins did not hold that dharmas were completely independent of each other, as the Mahavibhasa states: "conditioned dharmas are weak in their intrinsic nature, they can accomplish their activities only through mutual dependence" and "they have no sovereignty (aisvarya).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Svabhava in the early Abhidhamma texts was then not a term which meant ontological independence, metaphysical essence or underlying substance, but simply referred to their characteristics, which are dependent on other conditions and qualities.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] According to Ronkin: "In the early Sarvāstivāda exegetical texts, then, svabhāva is used as an atemporal, invariable criterion determining what a dharma is, not necessarily that a dharma exists.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Sautrantika school accepted the doctrine of svabhāva as referring to the distinctive or main characteristic of a dharma, but rejected the view that they exist in all three times .
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Buddhist philosopher Dharmakirti uses the concept of svabhāva, though he interprets it as being based on causal powers.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Other early Buddhist schools did not accept the svabhava concept, instead positing a kind of nominalism or conceptualism (*prajñaptivada*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This view was widespread among the Mahasamghika Nikaya.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] One school was even called "Prajñaptivada" because of their denial of the ultimate reality of all dharmas and their view that all dharmas are characterized by *prajñapti* (provisional designation or fictitious construction).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Another school called the Vainasikas also held that all dharmas were without svabhava.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] According to Paramārtha (499–569), another school, the Ekavyavahārikas held "that both the mundane and the supramundane factors [dharmas] are merely nominal (*prajñapti*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] They therefore claimed that all factors have no real essence, and that hence the same name applies to all [dharmas]." This helps to explain their name as “Ekavyavahārika” (those who propound the single meaning).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Paramārtha also notes that the Lokottaravāda school held "that the mundane factors have arisen from perversion (viparyāsa) and are only nominal (prajñapti)." However, in contrast to the other schools, they also held that the supramundane dharmas (nirvana etc.) were not nominal but real.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This view that dharmas are empty or void is also found in the *Lokānuvartana-sūtra* (‘The Sutra of Conformity with the World’, Taisho No.807) which survives in Chinese and Tibetan translation, and may have been a scripture of the Purvasailas, which was a sub-school of the Mahasamghika.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Another important project for the Abhidharmikas was to outline a theory of causality, especially of how momentary dharmas relate to each other through causes and conditions.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvastivadin analysis focused on six causes (*hetu*), four conditions (*pratyaya*) and five effects (*phala*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Dhammajoti, for the Sarvastivada school, 'causal efficacy is the central criterion for the reality/existence (astitva) of a dharma' and hence they were also sometimes called the 'Hetuvada' school.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] A dharma is real because it is a cause and it has effects, if it had no causal efficacy, it would not exist.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The last book of the Pali Abhidhamma, the Patthana, sets out the main Theravada theory on conditioned relations and causality.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Patthana is an exhaustive examination of the conditioned nature (Paticcasamupada) of all dhammas.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The introduction begins with a detailed list of 24 specific types of conditioned relationships (paccaya) that may pertain between different factors.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The majority of these conditions have counterparts in the Sarvāstivāda Abhidharma.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Pali Abhidhammatthasangaha reduces them all to four main types.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Sautrāntika school used a theory of 'seeds' (bīja) in the mental continuum to explain causal interaction between past and present dharmas, this theory was later developed by the Yogacara school in their theory of “storehouse consciousness” (ālayavijñāna).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] A prominent argument between the Abhidharmikas was on the Philosophy of time.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvāstivādin tradition held the view (expressed in the Vijñanakaya) that dharmas exist in all three times – past, present, future; hence the name of their school means "theory of all exists".
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Sautrāntika, Vibhajyavāda and Theravada schools argued against this eternalist view in favor of presentism (only the present moment exists).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This argument was so central, that north Indian Buddhist schools were often named according to their philosophical position.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] "Those who hold 'all exists' — the past, the present and the future — belong to the Sarvāstivāda.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Vasubandhu initially wrote in favor of Sarvāstivāda, and later critiqued this position.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvāstivāda-Vaibhāṣika also held an atomistic conception of time which divided time into discrete indivisible moments (kṣaṇa) and saw all events as lasting only for a minute instant (and yet also existing in all three times).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Theravadins also held a theory of momentariness (Khāṇavāda), but it was less ontological than Sarvāstivāda and more focused on the psychological aspects of time.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Theravada divided every dhamma into three different instants of origination (uppādakkhaṇa), endurance (ṭhitikkhaṇa) and cessation (bhaṅgakkhaṇa).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] They also held that only mental events were momentary, material events could endure for longer.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] A key problem which the Abhidharmikas wished to tackle was the question of how rebirth and karma works if there is no self to be reborn apart from the five aggregates.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Patthana includes the earliest Pali canonical reference to an important answer to this question: bhavanga, or 'life-continuum'.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This problem was also taken up by a group of Buddhist schools termed the Pudgalavadins or "Personalists" which included the Vātsīputrīya, the Dharmottarīya, the Bhadrayānīya, the Sammitiya and the Shannagarika.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] These schools posited the existence of a 'person' (pudgala) or self, which had a real existence that was not reducible to streams and collections of dharmas.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] They also often used other terms to refer to this real 'self', such as 'Atman' and 'Jiva' which are words for the immortal soul in Hinduism and Jainism respectively.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] They seemed to have held that the 'self' was part of a fifth category of existence, the “inexpressible”.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This was a radically different view than the not-self view held by the mainstream Buddhist schools and this theory was a major point of controversy and was thoroughly attacked by other Buddhist schools such as the Theravadins, Sarvastivadins and later Mahayanists.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvastivadin Abhidharmikas also developed the novel idea of an intermediate state between death and the next rebirth.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Purvasaila, Sammitiya, Vatsiputriya, and later Mahisasaka schools accepted this view, while the Theravadins, Vibhajyavada, Mahasanghika, and the Sariputrabhidharmasastra of the Dharmaguptakas rejected it.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Some Abhidharmikas such as the Sarvastivadins also defended an atomic theory.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] However unlike the Hindu Vaisheshika school, Abhidharmic atoms (paramannu) are not permanent, but momentary.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Vaibhasika held that an atom is the smallest analyzable unit of matter (rupa), hence it is a 'conceptual atom' (prajnapti-paramanu), though this also corresponds to a real existing thing.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] "An atom (paramänu) is the smallest rüpa.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] It cannot be cut, broken, penetrated; it cannot be taken up, abandoned, ridden on, stepped on, struck or dragged.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] It is neither long nor short, square nor round, regular nor irregular, convex nor concave.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] It has no smaller parts; it cannot be decomposed, cannot be seen, heard, smelled, touched.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The *Abhidhamma Piṭaka* is the third pitaka, or basket, of the Tipitaka (Sanskrit: *Tripiṭaka*), the canon of the Theravāda school.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The *Abhidhamma Piṭaka*, like the rest of the Theravāda *Tipiṭaka*, was orally transmitted until the 1st century BCE.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Due to famines and constant wars, the monks responsible for recording the oral tradition felt that there was a risk of portions of the canon being lost so the Abhidhamma was written down for the first time along with the rest of the Pāli Canon in the first century BCE.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The books of the *Abhidhamma Piṭaka* were translated into English in the 20th century and published by the Pāli Text Society.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] In addition to the canonical Abhidharma, Pali literature includes a variety of Abhidhamma commentaries and introductory manuals written after the compilation of the *Abhidhamma Piṭaka*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] These post-canonical texts attempted to expand and further clarify the analysis presented in the Abhidhamma.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The most influential of these commentaries are those of Buddhaghosa (c.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] 5th century) a South Indian exegete and philosopher who moved to Sri Lanka and wrote various commentaries and treatises in Pali.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] His *Visuddhimagga* ("Path of Purification") is a comprehensive manual of Buddhist practice that also contains an overview of the Abhidhamma.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This text remains one of the most popular Abhidhamma influenced texts in Theravada.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Sri Lankan Theravādins also composed shorter introductory manuals to the Abhidhamma.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The most popular and widely used of these remains the *Abhidhammatthasangaha* (*Compendium of the Topics of the Abhidharma*) by Anuruddha (circa 8th to 12th century).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] A further period of medieval Sri Lankan scholarship also produced a series of texts called the *sub-commentaries* (which are commentaries to the commentaries).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Abhidhamma remains a living tradition in Theravāda nations today and modern Abhidhamma works continue to be written in modern languages such as Burmese and Sinhala.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Abhidhamma studies are particularly stressed in Myanmar, where it has been the primary subject of study since around the 17th century.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] One of the most important figures in modern Myanmar Buddhism, Ledi Sayadaw (1846–1923), was well known for his writings on Abhidhamma (especially his commentary on the *Abhidhammatthasangaha,* called the *Paramatthadipanitika*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The most influential Indian Abhidharma tradition was that of the Sarvāstivāda Vaibhāṣika school, which was dominant in North India, especially Kashmir and also in Bactria and Gandhara.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This is the Abhidharma tradition that is studied in East Asian Buddhism and also in Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Like the Theravada Abhidharma, the Sarvāstivāda *Abhidharma Pitaka* also consists of seven texts, but they are quite different works, unlike the Sarvāstivāda Agamas, which are very close, often identical, to the suttas of the Theravada *Sutta Pitaka*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] According to Frauwallner however, the two Abhidharma collections share an "ancient core", which is basically an early doctrinal list of dharmas.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The core canonical work of this school, the *Jñānaprasthāna* ('Foundation of Knowledge'), also known as *Aṣṭaskandha* or *Aṣṭagrantha,* was said to be composed by master Kātyāyanīputra.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This became the basis for the *Abhidharma Mahāvibhāṣa Śāstra* ("Great Commentary"), an encyclopedic work which became the central text of the Vaibhāṣika tradition who became the Kasmiri Sarvāstivāda Orthodoxy under the patronage of the Kushan Empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Despite numerous variations and doctrinal disagreements within the tradition, most Sarvāstivāda-Vaibhāṣikas were united in their acceptance of the doctrine of "*sarvāstitva*" (all exists), which says that all phenomena in the three times (past, present and future) can be said to exist.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Another defining Vaibhāṣika doctrine was that of simultaneous causation (*sahabhū-hetu*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] In addition to the core Vaibhāṣika Abhidharma literature, a variety of expository texts or treatises were written to serve as overviews and introductions to the Abhidharma.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The oldest one of these was the *Abhidharma-hṛdaya-sastra* (*The Heart of Abhidharma*), by the Tocharian Dharmasresthin, (c.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This text became the model for most of the later treatises.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The most influential of these treatises however, is certainly the *Abhidharmakośabhāsya* (*Treasury of Higher Knowledge*, 5th century), a series of verses and accompanying commentary by Vasubandhu.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] It often critiques Vaibhāṣika views from a Sautrantika perspective.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Sautrantikas were a dissent group within the Sarvāstivāda tradition that rejected many of the core Vaibhāṣika views.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This text remains the main source for Abhidharma in Indo-Tibetan and East Asian Buddhism.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The most mature and refined form of Vaibhāṣika philosophy can be seen in the work of master Saṃghabhadra (ca fifth century CE), "undoubtedly one of the most brilliant Abhidharma masters in India".
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] His two main works, the **Nyāyānusāra* (*Shun zhengli lun* 順正理論) and the **Abhidharmasamayapradīpikā* (*Apidamo xian zong lun* 阿毘達磨顯宗論), are key sources of late Vaibhāṣika Abhidharma.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The *Śāriputra Abhidharma Śāstra* (舍利弗阿毘曇論 *Shèlìfú Āpítán Lùn*) (T.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] 1548) is a complete abhidharma text that is thought to come from the Dharmaguptaka sect.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The only complete edition of this text is that in Chinese.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Sanskrit fragments from this text have been found in Bamiyan, Afghanistan, and are now part of the Schøyen Collection (MS 2375/08).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The manuscripts at this find are thought to have been part of a monastery library of the Mahāsāṃghika Lokottaravāda sect.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Several Pudgalavada Abhidharma type texts also survive in Chinese, such as the *Traidharmakasastra* (Taisho no.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] 15c-30a) and the *Sammatiyanikayasastra.* These texts contain traditional Abhidharma type lists and doctrines, but they also expound and defend the Pudgalavada doctrine of the "person" (*pudgala*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Many Abhidharma texts have been lost—likely more than have survived.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This includes texts brought from India by Xuanzang belonging to a variety of Indian schools that were never translated into Chinese.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Many Abhidharma sastras discovered among the Gandharan Buddhist texts have no parallel in existing Indic languages or Chinese or Tibetan translation, suggesting the former breadth of Abhidharma literature.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] According to some sources, abhidharma was not accepted as canonical by the Mahāsāṃghika school.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The Theravādin *Dīpavaṃsa*, for example, records that the Mahāsāṃghikas had no abhidharma.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] However, other sources indicate that there were such collections of abhidharma.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] During the early 5th century, the Chinese pilgrim Faxian is said to have found a Mahāsāṃghika Abhidharma at a monastery in Pāṭaliputra.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] When Xuanzang visited Dhānyakaṭaka, he wrote that the monks of this region were Mahāsāṃghikas, and mentions the Pūrvaśailas specifically.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Near Dhānyakaṭaka, he met two Mahāsāṃghika bhikṣus and studied Mahāsāṃghika abhidharma with them for several months, during which time they also studied various Mahāyāna śāstras together under Xuanzang's direction.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] On the basis of textual evidence as well as inscriptions at Nāgārjunakoṇḍā, Joseph Walser concludes that at least some Mahāsāṃghika sects probably had an abhidharma collection, and that it likely contained five or six books.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The *Tattvasiddhi Śāstra* ("the treatise that accomplishes reality"; Chinese: 成實論, *Chéngshílun*), is an extant Abhidharma text which was popular in Chinese Buddhism.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This Abhidharma is now contained in the Chinese Buddhist canon, in sixteen fascicles (Taishō Tripiṭaka 1646).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Its authorship is attributed to Harivarman, a third-century monk from central India.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This work may belong to the Mahāsāṃghika Bahuśrutīya school or to the Sautrāntika school.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Paramārtha cites this Bahuśrutīya abhidharma as containing a combination of Hīnayāna and Mahāyāna doctrines, and Joseph Walser agrees that this assessment is correct.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] Ian Charles Harris also characterizes the text as a synthesis of Hīnayāna and Mahāyāna, and notes that its doctrines are very close to those in Mādhyamaka and Yogācāra works.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The *Tattvasiddhi Śāstra* maintained great popularity in Chinese Buddhism, and even lead to the formation of its own school of Buddhism in China, the *Chéngshí school* (成實宗), which was founded in 412 CE.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The *Chéngshí* School taught a progression of twenty-seven stations for cultivating realization, based upon the teachings of this text.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] They took Harivarman as its founder in India, and Kumārajīva as the school's founder in China.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] The *Chéngshí* School is counted among the ten schools of Tang dynasty Buddhism.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] From China, the *Chéngshí* School was transmitted to Japan in 625 CE, where it was known as *Jōjitsu-shu* (成實宗).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p01] This school is known as one of the six great schools of Japanese Buddhism in the Nara period (710–794 CE).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p02] Another complete system of Abhidharma thought is elaborated in certain works of the Mahāyāna Yogācāra tradition (which mainly evolved out of the Sarvāstivāda Abhidharma).
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p02] This Yogācāra Abhidharma can be found in the works of figures like Asanga, Vasubandhu, Sthiramati, Dharmapāla, Śīlabhadra, Xuanzang (Hsüan-tsang), and Vinītadeva.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p02] Yogācārins developed an Abhidharma literature set within a Mahāyāna framework.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p02] The *Prajñāpāramitā* sutras and associated literature are influenced by Abhidharma.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p02] These texts make use of Abhidharma categories (like the dharma theory), and adopt them or critique them in different ways.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p02] According to Edward Conze, the *Prajñāpāramitā* sutras were meant to be a criticism of the view held by some of the Abhidharmikas which saw dharmas as real.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p02] Conze also notes that the later *Prajñāpāramitā* sutras have been expanded by the insertion of various doctrinal Abhidharma lists.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p02] There is also plenty of Abhidharma material (mainly Sarvāstivāda) in the *Dà zhìdù lùn* (*The Treatise on the Great Prajñāpāramitā*; Chinese: 大智度論, *Mahāprajñāpāramitāupadeśa** Taishō Tripiṭaka no.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p02] The *Dà zhìdù lùn* was translated into Chinese by Kumārajīva (344–413 CE) and his student Sengrui.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p02] The work claims it is written by Nāgārjuna (c.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p02] 2nd century), but various scholars such as Étienne Lamotte and Paul Demiéville, have questioned this, holding that the author was instead a Sarvāstivāda monk learned in Abhidharma who became a Mahāyānist and wrote this text.
[src:ancient-philosophy/abhidharma-p02] It is a very influential text in East Asian Buddhism.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] According to Hegel, being is ultimately comprehensible only as an all-inclusive whole (*das Absolute*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Hegel asserted that in order for the thinking subject (human reason or consciousness) to be able to know its object (the world) at all, there must be in some sense an identity of thought and being.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Otherwise, the subject would never have access to the object and we would have no certainty about any of our knowledge of the world.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] The absolute idealist position dominated philosophy in nineteenth-century Britain and Germany, while exerting significantly less influence in the United States.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] The absolute idealist position should be distinguished from the subjective idealism of Berkeley, the transcendental idealism of Immanuel Kant, or the post-Kantian **critical idealism** (or post-Kantian transcendental idealism) of J.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] For Hegel, the interaction of opposites generates, in a dialectical fashion, all concepts necessary to comprehend what is.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] For Kant, reason was only for us, and the categories only emerged within the subject.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] However, for Hegel, reason is fully immanent.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Spirit emerges from nature in history and, in art, religion, and philosophy, knows itself in its truth.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Hegel shows that the world is not other than self.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] With the realization that mind and world are, by logical necessity, meaningfully coherent, our access to the world is made secure, a security that was lost in Kant's proclamation that the thing-in-itself was ultimately inaccessible.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] In both Schelling and Hegel's systems (especially the latter), the project aims towards a completion of metaphysics.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] As Redding describes it: "While opinions divide as to how Hegel's approach to logic relates to that of Kant, it is important to grasp that for Hegel logic is not simply a science of the form of our thoughts.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] For Schelling, reason was an organic 'striving' in nature, and this striving was one in which the subject and the object approached an identity.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Hegel's doubts about intellectual intuition's ability to prove or legitimate that the particular is in identity with whole led him to progressively formulate a speculative dialectic in which concepts like *Aufhebung* came to be articulated.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Hegel's innovation in German Idealism was to theorize a historical mode of self-consciousness self-reflection capable of generating a more inclusively holistic understanding of what it ultimately means to be rational in the grand scheme of things.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] By the beginning of the 19th century, German idealist philosophy, particularly that of Kant, Hegel, and Fichte, was being read by British philosophers.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Figures such as Samuel Taylor Coleridge, Thomas Carlyle and J.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Ferrier found in idealism an alternative and a response to the then-dominant empiricist views in Britain.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Early authors such as James Hutchison Stirling not only attempted to introduce German idealist thought to Britain, but sought to present their own version of absolute idealism in an English medium.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Green were of the first generation of British idealists who took the work of Hegel and some of his successors and, from their positions as professors at the universities of Glasgow and Oxford, respectively, influenced generations of students.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Absolute idealism was more fully developed in a second generation by their students, especially F.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Bradley's 1893 *Appearance and Reality* and Bosanquet's two volumes of Gifford lectures, *The Principle of Individuality and Value* (1912) and *The Value and Destiny of the Individual* were the most influential volumes of absolute idealism of the period.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] British absolute idealism had an influence not only within philosophy, but in theology, politics, and social and public policy.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Moreover, many of the students of the idealists, in turn, introduced absolute idealism to Canada, southern Africa, and India.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Neo-idealism in Italy took on different characteristics from its English counterpart.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Among its exponents were Guido De Ruggiero, a supporter of social liberalism, and above all Benedetto Croce, who articulated idealism in a historicist sense, and Giovanni Gentile, who theorized an actual idealism, which he saw embodied in the fascist state.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Gentile made a pivotal distinction to factors concerning Idealism's own criteria for reality, which have stood since Berkeley's adage «*esse est percipi*» by distinguishing between the concrete real «act of thinking», and the abstract «static thought».
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] For him, only in "thinking in action" is dialectical self-consciousness that includes everything.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] So Gentile transfused he whole reality of nature, history and spirit in the pure act of thought.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Every thing exists only in the mental act of thinking it: there are no single empirical entities separated from the trascendental consciousness; even the past lives only in the actual, present moment of memory.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Absolute idealism has greatly altered the philosophical landscape.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] This influence is mostly felt in the strong opposition it engendered.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Both logical positivism and analytic philosophy grew out of a rebellion against Hegelianism prevalent in England during the 19th century.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Continental phenomenology, existentialism, and postmodernism also seek to 'free themselves from Hegel's thought'.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Geoffrey Warnock, writing after the demise of absolute idealism as a philosophical movement in Britain, wrote that the absolute idealists were motivated by emotional concerns, which he says Bradley and McTaggart admitted.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] He also criticized them for vagueness and overreliance on rhetoric as opposed to argument, he added that in the writings of some "solemnity and unclarity seem to rise not seldom to the pitch of actual fraud".
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] Martin Heidegger, one of the leading figures of Continental philosophy in the 20th century, sought to distance himself from Hegel's work.
[src:ancient-philosophy/absolute-idealism] One of Heidegger's philosophical themes in *Being and Time* was "overcoming metaphysics," aiming to distinguish his book from Hegelian tracts.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] Greek philosophical skepticism, as a distinct philosophical movement, began with Pyrrho of Elis (c.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] 270 BCE), with antecedents in Xenophanes and Democritus.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] His followers, the Pyrrhonists, pointed out the problem of the criterion: that our theories and our sense impressions are unable to accurately distinguish truth from falsehood; therefore we must suspend judgment (*epoche*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] They were consistent enough to extend their doubt even to their own principle of doubt, making their skepticism universal, thus escaping reproach for basing it upon a fresh dogmatism.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] Mental imperturbability (*ataraxia*) was the result to be attained by cultivating such a frame of mind.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] Around 266 BCE, Arcesilaus became head of the Platonic Academy.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] He adopted skepticism as a central tenet of Platonism, making Platonism nearly the same as Pyrrhonism.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] After Arcesilaus, the Academics diverged from Pyrrhonism.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] This skeptical period of ancient Platonism, from Arcesilaus to Philo of Larissa, became known as the new Academy, although some ancient authors added further subdivisions, such as a middle Academy.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] Following the death of the Pyrrhonist Timon of Phlius, the Platonic Academy became the primary advocate of skepticism until the mid-first century BCE.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] The Academics did not doubt the existence of truth; they just doubted that humans had the capacities for obtaining it.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] They based this position on Plato's *Phaedo*, in which Socrates discusses how knowledge is not accessible to mortals.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] While the objective of the Pyrrhonists was the attainment of ataraxia, after Arcesilaus the Academics did not hold up ataraxia as the central objective.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] The Academics focused on criticizing the dogmas of other schools of philosophy, in particular of the dogmatism of the Stoics.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] They acknowledged some vestiges of a moral law within, at best merely a plausible guide, the possession of which, however, formed the real distinction between the sage and the fool.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] Slight as the difference may appear between the positions of the Academics and the Pyrrhonists, a comparison of their lives leads to the conclusion that a practical philosophical moderation was the characteristic of the Academics whereas the objectives of the Pyrrhonists were more psychological.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] Up to Arcesilaus, the Platonic Academy accepted the principle of finding a general unity in all things, by the aid of which a principle of certainty might be found.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] The doctrines of Arcesilaus, which must be gathered from the writings of others, represent an attack on the Stoic *phantasia kataleptike* (criterion) and are based on the skepticism which was latent in the later writings of Plato.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] Arcesilaus held that strength of intellectual conviction cannot be regarded as valid, inasmuch as it is characteristic equally of contradictory convictions.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] The uncertainty of sense data applies equally to the conclusions of reason, and therefore man must be content with probability which is sufficient as a practical guide.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] "We know nothing, not even our ignorance"; therefore the wise man will be content with an agnostic attitude.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] The next stage in Academic skepticism was the moderate skepticism of Carneades, which he said owed its existence to his opposition to Chrysippus.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] All our sensations are relative, and acquaint us, not with things as they are, but only with the impressions that things produce upon us.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] Experience, he said, clearly shows that there is no true impression.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] There is no notion that may not deceive us; it is impossible to distinguish between false and true impressions; therefore the Stoic *phantasia kataleptike* must be given up.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] There is no phantasia kataleptike ("criterion") of truth.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] Carneades also assailed Stoic theology and physics.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] In answer to the doctrine of final cause, of design in nature, he pointed to those things which cause destruction and danger to man, to the evil committed by men endowed with reason, to the miserable condition of humanity, and to the misfortunes that assail the good man.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] There is, he concluded, no evidence for the doctrine of a divine superintending providence.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] Even if there were orderly connexion of parts in the universe, this may have resulted quite naturally.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] No proof can be advanced to show that this world is anything but the product of natural forces.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] Knowledge being impossible, a wise man should practice *epoche* (suspension of judgment).
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] He will not even be sure that he can be sure of nothing.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] He saved himself, however, from absolute skepticism by the doctrine of plausibility, which may serve as a practical guide in life.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] Ideas or notions are never true, but only plausible; nevertheless, there are degrees of plausibility, and hence degrees of belief, leading to action.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] According to Carneades, an impression may be plausible in itself; plausible and uncontradicted (not distracted by synchronous sensations, but shown to be in harmony with them) when compared with others; plausible, uncontradicted, and thoroughly investigated and confirmed.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] In the first degree there is a strong persuasion of the propriety of the impression made; the second and third degrees are produced by comparisons of the impression with others associated with it, and an analysis of itself.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] Carneades left no written works; his opinions seem to have been systematized by his pupil Clitomachus, whose works, which included one "on suspension of judgment", were made use of by Cicero.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] In Philo of Larissa, we find a tendency not only to reconcile the internal divergences of the Academy itself, but also to connect it with parallel systems of thought.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] In general, his philosophy was a reaction against the skeptic or agnostic position of the middle and new Academy in favor of the dogmatism of Plato.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] Philo of Larissa endeavored to show that Carneades was not opposed to Plato, and further that the apparent antagonism between Platonism and Stoicism was because they were arguing from different points of view.
[src:ancient-philosophy/academic-skepticism] From this syncretism emerged the eclectic middle Platonism of Antiochus of Ascalon, the last product of Academic development.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The **Achaemenid Empire** (/ə.ˈkiː.mə.nɪd/, *ə-KEE-mə-nid*; Old Persian: 𐎧𐏁𐏂, *Xšāça*, lit.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] 'The Empire' or 'The Kingdom') was an ancient Iranian empire founded by Cyrus the Great of the Achaemenid dynasty in 550 BC.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] At peak, its territorial extent was roughly 5.5 million square kilometres (2.1 million square miles), making it the largest empire of its time.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Based in the Iranian plateau, it stretched from the Balkans and Cyrenaica in the west to the Indus Valley in the east, including Anatolia, Cyprus, Mesopotamia, the Levant, the South Caucasus, parts of Eastern Arabia, and large parts of Central Asia.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the 7th century BC, the region of Persis, located in the southwestern part of the Iranian plateau, had been settled by Persian people.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persis, Cyrus rose and defeated Media, Lydia, and the Neo-Babylonian Empire, thus marking the establishment of a new imperial polity in the ancient Near East.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] While its conquests were largely successful in most regions, the Achaemenid Empire's attempts to expand into Greece proved extremely difficult over the course of decades of wars and multiple kings, ultimately resulting in its defeat in the Greek mainland.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 330 BC, amidst a Greek military campaign that began in 336 BC, the Achaemenid Empire was conquered in its entirety by Alexander the Great, who annexed it to his Macedonian Empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death, which sparked the beginning of the Hellenistic period in 323 BC, the majority of the former Achaemenid Empire's territories came under the rule of the Seleucid Empire and the Ptolemaic Kingdom.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Almost a century later, Iranian elites in the central plateau successfully reclaimed power from the Seleucids and established the Parthian Empire, which existed for nearly half a millennium before being succeeded by the Iranian Sasanian Empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of these systems were adopted and expanded upon by later empires in the Greco-Roman world and beyond.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is named after Achaemenes, who is credited as the progenitor of the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The term *Achaemenid* means "of the family of the Achaemenis/Achaemenes" (Old Persian: 𐏃𐎧𐎠𐎶𐎴𐎡𐏁, romanized: *Haxāmaniš*; a bahuvrihi compound translating to "having a friend's mind").
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Achaemenes was himself a minor seventh-century ruler of the Anshan in southwestern Iran, and a vassal of Assyria.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Around 850 BC the original nomadic people who began the empire called themselves the *Parsa* and their constantly shifting territory *Parsua*, for the most part localized around Persis.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The name "Persia" is a Greek and Latin pronunciation of the native word referring to the country of the people originating from Persis (Old Persian: 𐎱𐎠𐎼𐎿, romanized: *Pārsa*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian term 𐎧𐏁𐏂 *Xšāça*, literally meaning "The Kingdom", was used to refer to the Empire formed by their multinational state.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire was created by nomadic Persians.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were Iranian people who arrived in what is today Iran c.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] 1000 BC and settled a region including north-western Iran, the Zagros Mountains and Persis alongside the native Elamites.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were originally nomadic pastoralists in the western Iranian Plateau.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire may not have been the first Iranian empire, as the Medes, another group of Iranian people, possibly established a short-lived empire when they played a major role in overthrowing the Assyrians.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids were initially rulers of the Elamite city of Anshan near the modern city of Marvdasht; the title "King of Anshan" was an adaptation of the earlier Elamite title "King of Susa and Anshan".
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] There are conflicting accounts of the identities of the earliest Kings of Anshan.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Cyrus Cylinder (the oldest extant genealogy of the Achaemenids) the kings of Anshan were Teispes, Cyrus I, Cambyses I and Cyrus II, also known as Cyrus the Great, who founded the empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The later Behistun Inscription, written by Darius the Great, claims that Teispes was the son of Achaemenes and that Darius is also descended from Teispes through a different line, but no earlier texts mention Achaemenes.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In Herodotus' Histories, he writes that Cyrus the Great was the son of Cambyses I and Mandane of Media, the daughter of Astyages, the king of the Median Empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus revolted against the Median Empire in 553 BC, and in 550 BC succeeded in defeating the Medes, capturing Astyages and taking the Median capital city of Ecbatana.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Once in control of Ecbatana, Cyrus styled himself as the successor to Astyages and assumed control of the entire empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] By inheriting Astyages' empire, he also inherited the territorial conflicts the Medes had with both Lydia and the Neo-Babylonian Empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] King Croesus of Lydia sought to take advantage of the new international situation by advancing into what had previously been Median territory in Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus led a counterattack which not only fought off Croesus' armies, but also led to the capture of Sardis and the fall of the Lydian Kingdom in 546 BC.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus placed Pactyes in charge of collecting tribute in Lydia and left, but once Cyrus had left Pactyes instigated a rebellion against Cyrus.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus sent the Median general Mazares to deal with the rebellion, and Pactyes was captured.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mazares, and after his death Harpagus, set about reducing all the cities which had taken part in the rebellion.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Lydia took about four years in total.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the power in Ecbatana changed hands from the Medes to the Persians, many tributaries to the Median Empire believed their situation had changed and revolted against Cyrus.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This forced Cyrus to fight wars against Bactria and the nomadic Saka in Central Asia.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] During these wars, Cyrus established several garrison towns in Central Asia, including the Cyropolis.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nothing is known of Persia–Babylon relations between 547 and 539 BC, but it is likely that there were hostilities between the two empires for several years leading up to the war of 540–539 BC and the Fall of Babylon.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In October 539 BC, Cyrus won a battle against the Babylonians at Opis, then took Sippar without a fight before finally capturing the city of Babylon on 12 October, where the Babylonian king Nabonidus was taken prisoner.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus is credited with freeing the Jews from the Babylonian captivity, permitting their return to Judah, and authorizing the rebuilding of Jerusalem, including the Second Temple.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 530 BC, Cyrus died and was succeeded by his eldest son Cambyses II, while his younger son Bardiya received a large territory in Central Asia.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] By 525 BC, Cambyses had successfully subjugated Phoenicia and Cyprus and was making preparations to invade Egypt with the newly created Persian navy.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Pharaoh Amasis II had died in 526, and had been succeeded by Psamtik III, resulting in the defection of key Egyptian allies to the Persians.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Psamtik positioned his army at Pelusium in the Nile Delta.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He was soundly defeated by the Persians in the Battle of Pelusium before fleeing to Memphis, where the Persians defeated him and took him prisoner.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After attempting a failed revolt, Psamtik III promptly committed suicide.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus depicts Cambyses as openly antagonistic to the Egyptian people and their gods, cults, temples, and priests, in particular stressing the murder of the sacred bull Apis.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He says that these actions led to a madness that caused him to kill his brother Bardiya (who Herodotus says was killed in secret), his own sister-wife and Croesus of Lydia.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then concludes that Cambyses completely lost his mind, and all later classical authors repeat the themes of Cambyses' impiety and madness.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, this is based on spurious information, as the epitaph of Apis from 524 BC shows that Cambyses participated in the funeral rites of Apis styling himself as pharaoh.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following the conquest of Egypt, the Libyans and the Greeks of Cyrene and Barca in present-day eastern Libya (Cyrenaica) surrendered to Cambyses and sent tribute without a fight.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cambyses then planned invasions of Carthage, the oasis of Ammon and Ethiopia.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus claims that the naval invasion of Carthage was canceled because the Phoenicians, who made up a large part of Cambyses' fleet, refused to take up arms against their own people, but modern historians doubt whether an invasion of Carthage was ever planned at all.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, Cambyses dedicated his efforts to the other two campaigns, aiming to improve the Empire's strategic position in Africa by conquering the Kingdom of Meroë and taking strategic positions in the western oases.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] To this end, he established a garrison at Elephantine consisting mainly of Jewish soldiers, who remained stationed at Elephantine throughout Cambyses' reign.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Furthermore, in two inscriptions of Darius, Nubia is listed as one of the lands in the empire, and a Nubian delegation is depicted in Persepolis on the Apadana reliefs which visually present the lands of Darius’ empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] These suggest that Cambyses saw success in subduing Nubia.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The events surrounding Cambyses's death and Bardiya's succession are greatly debated as there are many conflicting accounts.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to Herodotus, as Bardiya's assassination had been committed in secret, the majority of Persians still believed him to be alive.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This allowed two Magi to rise up against Cambyses, with one of them sitting on the throne able to impersonate Bardiya because of their remarkable physical resemblance and shared name (Smerdis in Herodotus's accounts).
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ctesias writes that when Cambyses had Bardiya killed he immediately put the magus Sphendadates in his place as satrap of Bactria due to a remarkable physical resemblance.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Two of Cambyses' confidants then conspired to usurp Cambyses and put Sphendadates on the throne under the guise of Bardiya.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun Inscription, written by the following king Darius the Great, a magus named Gaumata impersonated Bardiya and incited a revolution in Persia.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Whatever the exact circumstances of the revolt, Cambyses heard news of it in the summer of 522 BC and began to return from Egypt, but he was wounded in the thigh in Syria and died of gangrene, so Bardiya's impersonator became king.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The account of Darius is the earliest, and although the later historians all agree on the key details of the story, that a magus impersonated Bardiya and took the throne, this may have been a story created by Darius to justify his own usurpation.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Iranologist Pierre Briant hypothesises that Bardiya was not killed by Cambyses, but waited until his death in the summer of 522 BC to claim his legitimate right to the throne as he was then the only male descendant of the royal family.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Briant says that although the hypothesis of a deception by Darius is generally accepted today, "nothing has been established with certainty at the present time, given the available evidence".
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun inscription, Gaumata ruled for seven months before being overthrown in 522 BC by Darius the Great (Old Persian *Dāryavuš*, "who holds firm the good", also known as *Darayarahush*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Magi, though persecuted, continued to exist, and a year following the death of the first pseudo-Smerdis (*Gaumata*), saw a second pseudo-Smerdis (*Vahyazdāta*) attempt a coup.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The coup, though initially successful, failed.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus writes that the native leadership debated the best form of government for the empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Macedonian king Amyntas I surrendered his country to the Persians in about 512–511.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Macedonia was part of Persian military operations initiated by Darius the Great (521–486) in 513—after immense preparations—a huge Achaemenid army invaded the Balkans and tried to defeat the European Scythians roaming to the north of the Danube river.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' army subjugated several Thracian people, and virtually all other regions that touch the European part of the Black Sea, such as parts of modern Bulgaria, Romania, Ukraine, and Russia, before it returned to Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius left in Europe one of his commanders named Megabazus whose task was to accomplish conquests in the Balkans.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian troops subjugated gold-rich Thrace, the coastal Greek cities, and defeated and conquered the powerful Paeonians.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Finally, Megabazus sent envoys to Amyntas, demanding acceptance of Persian domination, which the Macedonians did.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Balkans provided many soldiers for the multi-ethnic Achaemenid army.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of the Macedonian and Persian elite intermarried, such as the Persian official Bubares who married Amyntas' daughter, Gygaea.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Family ties that the Macedonian rulers Amyntas and Alexander enjoyed with Bubares ensured them good relations with the Persian kings Darius and Xerxes I, who was also known as Xerxes the Great.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian invasion led indirectly to Macedonia's rise in power and Persia had some common interests in the Balkans; with Persian aid, the Macedonians stood to gain much at the expense of some Balkan tribes such as the Paeonians and Greeks.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] All in all, the Macedonians were "willing and useful Persian allies.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Macedonian soldiers fought against Athens and Sparta in Xerxes I's army.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians referred to both Greeks and Macedonians as *Yauna* ("Ionians", their term for "Greeks"), and to Macedonians specifically as *Yaunã Takabara* or "Greeks with hats that look like shields", possibly referring to the Macedonian kausia hat.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt in 499 BC, and associated revolts in Aeolis, Doris, Cyprus, and Caria, were military rebellions by several regions of Asia Minor against Persian rule, lasting from 499 to 493 BC.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the heart of the rebellion was the dissatisfaction of the Greek cities of Asia Minor with the tyrants appointed by Persia to rule them, along with the individual actions of two Milesian tyrants, Histiaeus and Aristagoras.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 499 BC, the then-tyrant of Miletus, Aristagoras, launched a joint expedition with the Persian satrap Artaphernes to conquer Naxos, in an attempt to bolster his position in Miletus, both financially and in terms of prestige.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The mission was a debacle, and sensing his imminent removal as a tyrant, Aristagoras chose to incite the whole of Ionia into rebellion against the Persian king, Darius I, who was commonly known as Darius the Great.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians continued to reduce the cities along the west coast that still held out against them, before finally imposing a peace settlement in 493 BC on Ionia that was generally considered to be both just and fair.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt constituted the first major conflict between Greece and the Achaemenid Empire, and as such represents the first phase of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Asia Minor had been brought back into the Persian fold, but Darius had vowed to punish Athens and Eretria for their support of the revolt.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Moreover, seeing that the political situation in Greece posed a continued threat to the stability of his Empire, he decided to embark on the conquest of all of Greece.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The first campaign of the invasion was to bring the territories in the Balkan peninsula back within the empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian grip over these territories had loosened following the Ionian Revolt.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 492 BC, the Persian general Mardonius re-subjugated Thrace and made Macedonia a fully subordinate part of the empire; it had been a vassal as early as the late 6th century BC but retained a great deal of autonomy.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 490 BC the Persian forces were defeated by the Athenians at the Battle of Marathon and Darius I would die before having the chance to launch an invasion of Greece.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes I (485–465 BC, Old Persian *Xšayārša* "Hero Among Kings"), son of Darius I, vowed to complete the job.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He organized a massive invasion aiming to conquer Greece.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] His army entered Greece from the north in the spring of 480 BC, meeting little or no resistance through Macedonia and Thessaly, but was delayed by a small Greek force for three days at Thermopylae.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] A simultaneous naval battle of Artemisium was tactically indecisive as large storms destroyed ships from both sides.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was stopped prematurely when the Greeks received news of the defeat at Thermopylae and retreated.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was a tactical victory for the Persians, giving them uncontested control of Artemisium and the Aegean Sea.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following his victory at the Battle of Thermopylae, Xerxes sacked the evacuated city of Athens and prepared to meet the Greeks at the strategic Isthmus of Corinth and the Saronic Gulf.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 480 BC the Greeks won a decisive victory over the Persian fleet at the Battle of Salamis and forced Xerxes to retire to Sardis.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The land army which he left in Greece under Mardonius retook Athens but was eventually destroyed in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The final defeat of the Persians at Mycale encouraged the Greek cities of Asia to revolt, and the Persians lost all of their territories in Europe with Macedonia once again becoming independent.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes was assassinated in his bed, though ancient accounts conflict significantly.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The assassination is attributed by Greek and Roman sources to Artabanus, though a Babylonian tablet attributes it to Xerxes' son.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Xerxes I was assassinated, he was succeeded by his eldest surviving son Artaxerxes I.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was during his reign that Elamite ceased to be the language of government, and Aramaic gained in importance.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was probably during this reign that the solar calendar was introduced as the national calendar.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Artaxerxes I, Zoroastrianism became the *de facto* religion of the empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Persia had been defeated at the Battle of Eurymedon (469 or 466 BC), military action between Greece and Persia was halted.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes I took power, he introduced a new Persian strategy of weakening the Athenians by funding their enemies in Greece.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This indirectly caused the Athenians to move the treasury of the Delian League from the island of Delos to the Athenian acropolis.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This funding practice inevitably prompted renewed fighting in 450 BC, where the Greeks attacked at the Battle of Cyprus.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Cimon's failure to attain much in this expedition, the Peace of Callias was agreed between Athens, Argos and Persia in 449 BC.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes offered asylum to Themistocles, who was the winner of the Battle of Salamis, after Themistocles was ostracized from Athens.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, Artaxerxes gave him Magnesia, Myus, and Lampsacus to maintain him in bread, meat, and wine.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In addition, Artaxerxes I gave him Palaescepsis to provide him with clothes, and he also gave him Percote with bedding for his house.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes died in 424 BC at Susa, his body was taken to the tomb already built for him in the Naqsh-e Rustam Necropolis.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was Persian tradition that kings begin constructing their own tombs while they were still alive.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes I was immediately succeeded by his eldest and only legitimate son, Xerxes II.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, after a few days on the throne, he was assassinated while drunk by Pharnacyas and Menostanes on the orders of his illegitimate brother Sogdianus, who apparently had gained the support of his regions.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus reigned for six months and fifteen days before being captured by his half-brother, Ochus, who had rebelled against him.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus was executed by being suffocated in ash because Ochus had promised he would not die by the sword, by poison or by hunger.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ochus then took the royal name Darius II.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' ability to defend his position on the throne ended the short power vacuum.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] From 412 BC Darius II, at the insistence of Tissaphernes, gave support first to Athens, then to Sparta, but in 407 BC, Darius' son Cyrus the Younger was appointed to replace Tissaphernes and aid was given entirely to Sparta which finally defeated Athens in 404 BC.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the same year, Darius fell ill and died in Babylon.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] His death gave an Egyptian rebel named Amyrtaeus the opportunity to throw off Persian control over Egypt.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] At his death bed, Darius' Babylonian wife Parysatis pleaded with him to have her second eldest son Cyrus (the Younger) crowned, but Darius refused.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Queen Parysatis favoured Cyrus more than her eldest son Artaxerxes II.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Plutarch relates (probably on the authority of Ctesias) that the displaced Tissaphernes came to the new king on his coronation day to warn him that his younger brother Cyrus (the Younger) was preparing to assassinate him during the ceremony.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had Cyrus arrested and would have had him executed if their mother Parysatis had not intervened.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus was then sent back as Satrap of Lydia, where he prepared an armed rebellion.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus assembled a large army, including a contingent of Ten Thousand Greek mercenaries, and made his way deeper into Persia.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The army of Cyrus was stopped by the royal Persian army of Artaxerxes II at Cunaxa in 401 BC, where Cyrus was killed.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ten Thousand Greek Mercenaries including Xenophon were now deep in Persian territory and were at risk of attack.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] So they searched for others to offer their services to but eventually had to return to Greece.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II was the longest reigning of the Achaemenid kings and it was during this 45-year period of relative peace and stability that many of the monuments of the era were constructed.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes moved the capital back to Persepolis, which he greatly extended.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, the summer capital at Ecbatana was lavishly extended with gilded columns and roof tiles of silver and copper.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The extraordinary innovation of the Zoroastrian shrines can also be dated to his reign, and it was probably during this period that Zoroastrianism spread from Armenia throughout Asia Minor and the Levant.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The construction of temples, though serving a religious purpose, was not a purely selfless act, as they also served as an important source of income.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] From the Babylonian kings, the Achaemenids adopted the concept of a mandatory temple tax, a one-tenth tithe which all inhabitants paid to the temple nearest to their land or another source of income.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II became involved in a war with Persia's erstwhile allies, the Spartans, who, under Agesilaus II, invaded Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] To redirect the Spartans' attention to Greek affairs, Artaxerxes II subsidized their enemies: in particular the Athenians, Thebans and Corinthians.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] These subsidies helped to engage the Spartans in what would become known as the Corinthian War.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 387 BC, Artaxerxes II betrayed his allies and came to an arrangement with Sparta, and in the Treaty of Antalcidas he forced his erstwhile allies to come to terms.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This treaty restored control of the Greek cities of Ionia and Aeolis on the Anatolian coast to the Persians while giving Sparta dominance on the Greek mainland.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 385 BC he campaigned against the Cadusians.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although successful against the Greeks, Artaxerxes II had more trouble with the Egyptians, who had successfully revolted against him at the beginning of his reign.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] An attempt to reconquer Egypt in 373 BC was completely unsuccessful, but in his waning years the Persians did manage to defeat a joint Egyptian–Spartan effort to conquer Phoenicia.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He quashed the Revolt of the Satraps in 372–362 BC.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He is reported to have had a number of wives.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] His main wife was Stateira, until she was poisoned by Artaxerxes II's mother Parysatis in about 400 BC.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Another chief wife was a Greek woman of Phocaea named Aspasia (not the same as the concubine of Pericles).
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II is said to have had more than 115 sons from 350 wives.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 358 BC Artaxerxes II died and was succeeded by his son Artaxerxes III.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 355 BC, Artaxerxes III forced Athens to conclude a peace which required the city's forces to leave Asia Minor and to acknowledge the independence of its rebellious allies.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes started a campaign against the rebellious Cadusians, but he managed to appease both of the Cadusian kings.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] One individual who successfully emerged from this campaign was Darius Codomannus, who later occupied the Persian throne as Darius III.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III then ordered the disbanding of all the satrapal armies of Asia Minor, as he felt that they could no longer guarantee peace in the west and was concerned that these armies equipped the western satraps with the means to revolt.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The order was however ignored by Artabazos II of Phrygia, who asked for the help of Athens in a rebellion against the king.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes of Mysia also supported Artabazos and the combined forces managed to defeat the forces sent by Artaxerxes III in 354 BC.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 353 BC, they were defeated by Artaxerxes III's army and were disbanded.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes was pardoned by the king, while Artabazos fled to the safety of the court of Philip II of Macedon.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] 351 BC, Artaxerxes embarked on a campaign to recover Egypt, which had revolted under his father, Artaxerxes II.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the same time, a rebellion had broken out in Asia Minor, which, being supported by Thebes, threatened to become serious.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Levying a vast army, Artaxerxes invaded Egypt and engaged in fighting with Nectanebo II.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After a year of fighting the Egyptian Pharaoh, Nectanebo inflicted a crushing defeat on the Persians with the support of mercenaries led by the Greek generals Diophantus and Lamius.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes was compelled to retreat and postpone his plans to reconquer Egypt.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Soon after this defeat, there were rebellions in Phoenicia, Asia Minor and Cyprus.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] , with a label in Greek (ΔΑΡΕΙΟΣ, top right) giving his name.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes committed responsibility for the suppression of the Cyprian rebels to Idrieus, prince of Caria, who employed 8,000 Greek mercenaries and forty triremes, commanded by Phocion the Athenian, and Evagoras, son of the elder Evagoras, the Cypriot monarch.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes initiated a counter-offensive against Sidon by commanding Belesys, satrap of Syria, and Mazaeus, satrap of Cilicia, to invade the city and to keep the Phoenicians in check.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both satraps suffered crushing defeats at the hands of Tennes, the Sidonese king, who was aided by 40,000 Greek mercenaries sent to him by Nectanebo II and commanded by Mentor of Rhodes.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persian forces were driven out of Phoenicia.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this, Artaxerxes personally led an army of 330,000 men against Sidon.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes' army comprised 300,000-foot soldiers, 30,000 cavalry, 300 triremes, and 500 transports or provision ships.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After gathering this army, he sought assistance from the Greeks.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Though refused aid by Athens and Sparta, he succeeded in obtaining a thousand Theban heavy-armed hoplites under Lacrates, three thousand Argives under Nicostratus, and six thousand Æolians, Ionians, and Dorians from the Greek cities of Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Greek support was numerically small, amounting to no more than 10,000 men, but it formed, together with the Greek mercenaries from Egypt who went over to him afterward, the force on which he placed his chief reliance, and to which the ultimate success of his expedition was mainly due.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The approach of Artaxerxes sufficiently weakened the resolution of Tennes that he endeavoured to purchase his own pardon by delivering up 100 principal citizens of Sidon into the hands of the Persian king and then admitting Artaxerxes within the defences of the town.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had the 100 citizens transfixed with javelins, and when 500 more came out as supplicants to seek his mercy, Artaxerxes consigned them to the same fate.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sidon was then burnt to the ground, either by Artaxerxes or by the Sidonian citizens.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Forty thousand people died in the conflagration.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes sold the ruins at a high price to speculators, who calculated on reimbursing themselves by the treasures which they hoped to dig out from among the ashes.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tennes was later put to death by Artaxerxes.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes later sent Jews who supported the revolt to Hyrcania on the south coast of the Caspian Sea.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The reduction of Sidon was followed closely by the invasion of Egypt.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes III, in addition to his 330,000 Persians, had now a force of 14,000 Greeks furnished by the Greek cities of Asia Minor: 4,000 under Mentor, consisting of the troops that he had brought to the aid of Tennes from Egypt; 3,000 sent by Argos; and 1,000 from Thebes.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He divided these troops into three bodies, and placed at the head of each a Persian and a Greek.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Greek commanders were Lacrates of Thebes, Mentor of Rhodes and Nicostratus of Argos while the Persians were led by Rhossaces, Aristazanes, and Bagoas, the chief of the eunuchs.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II resisted with an army of 100,000 of whom 20,000 were Greek mercenaries.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II occupied the Nile and its various branches with his large navy.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The character of the country, intersected by numerous canals and full of strongly fortified towns, was in his favour and Nectanebo II might have been expected to offer a prolonged, if not even a successful resistance.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, he lacked good generals, and, over-confident in his own powers of command, he was out-maneuvered by the Greek mercenary generals, and his forces were eventually defeated by the combined Persian armies.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his defeat, Nectanebo hastily fled to Memphis, leaving the fortified towns to be defended by their garrisons.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] These garrisons consisted of partly Greek and partly Egyptian troops; between whom jealousies and suspicions were easily sown by the Persian leaders.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persians were able to rapidly reduce numerous towns across Lower Egypt and were advancing upon Memphis when Nectanebo decided to quit the country and flee southwards to Ethiopia.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian army completely routed the Egyptians and occupied the Lower Delta of the Nile.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Nectanebo fleeing to Ethiopia, all of Egypt submitted to Artaxerxes.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Jews in Egypt were sent either to Babylon or to the south coast of the Caspian Sea, the same location that the Jews of Phoenicia had earlier been sent.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this victory over the Egyptians, Artaxerxes had the city walls destroyed, started a reign of terror, and set about looting all the temples.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persia gained a significant amount of wealth from this looting.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes also raised high taxes and attempted to weaken Egypt enough that it could never revolt against Persia.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] For the 10 years that Persia controlled Egypt, believers in the native religion were persecuted and sacred books were stolen.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Before Artaxerxes returned to Persia, he appointed Pherendares as satrap of Egypt.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] With the wealth gained from his reconquering Egypt, Artaxerxes was able to amply reward his mercenaries.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then returned to his capital having successfully completed his invasion of Egypt.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his success in Egypt, Artaxerxes returned to Persia and spent the next few years effectively quelling insurrections in various parts of the Empire so that a few years after his conquest of Egypt, the Persian Empire was firmly under his control.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Egypt remained a part of the Persian Empire from then until Alexander the Great's conquest of Egypt.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] After the conquest of Egypt, there were no more revolts or rebellions against Artaxerxes.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor and Bagoas, the two generals who had most distinguished themselves in the Egyptian campaign, were advanced to posts of the highest importance.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor, who was governor of the entire Asiatic seaboard, was successful in reducing to subjection many of the chiefs who during the recent troubles had rebelled against Persian rule.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the course of a few years, Mentor and his forces were able to bring the whole Asian Mediterranean coast into complete submission and dependence.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas went back to the Persian capital with Artaxerxes, where he took a leading role in the internal administration of the Empire and maintained tranquillity throughout the rest of the Empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] During the last six years of the reign of Artaxerxes III, the Persian Empire was governed by a vigorous and successful government.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian forces in Ionia and Lycia regained control of the Aegean and the Mediterranean Sea and took over much of Athens' former island empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, Isocrates of Athens started giving speeches calling for a 'crusade against the barbarians' but there was not enough strength left in any of the Greek city-states to answer his call.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although there were no rebellions in the Persian Empire itself, the growing power and territory of Philip II of Macedon in Macedon (against which Demosthenes was in vain warning the Athenians) attracted the attention of Artaxerxes.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, he ordered that Persian influence was to be used to check and constrain the rising power and influence of the Macedonian kingdom.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 340 BC, a Persian force was dispatched to assist the Thracian prince, Cersobleptes, to maintain his independence.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sufficient effective aid was given to the city of Perinthus that the numerous and well-appointed army with which Philip had commenced his siege of the city was compelled to give up the attempt.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the last year of Artaxerxes' rule, Philip II already had plans in place for an invasion of the Persian Empire, which would crown his career, but the Greeks would not unite with him.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 338 BC Artaxerxes was poisoned by Bagoas with the assistance of a physician.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III was succeeded by Artaxerxes IV Arses, who before he could act was also poisoned by Bagoas.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas is further said to have killed not only all Arses' children, but many of the other princes of the land.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas then placed Darius III, a nephew of Artaxerxes IV, on the throne.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III, previously the Satrap of Armenia, personally forced Bagoas to swallow poison.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 334 BC, when Darius was just succeeding in subduing Egypt again, Alexander and his battle-hardened troops invaded Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander the Great (Alexander III of Macedon) defeated the Persian armies at Granicus (334 BC), followed by Issus (333 BC), and lastly at Gaugamela (331 BC).
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Afterwards, he marched on Susa and Persepolis which surrendered and was destroyed by fire in early 330 BC.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persepolis, Alexander headed north to Pasargadae, where he visited the tomb of Cyrus, the man whom he had heard of from the *Cyropaedia*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the ensuing chaos created by Alexander's invasion of Persia, Cyrus's tomb was broken into and most of its luxuries were looted.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Alexander reached the tomb, he was horrified by the manner in which it had been treated, and questioned the Magi, putting them on trial.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] By some accounts, Alexander's decision to put the Magi on trial was more an attempt to undermine their influence and display his own power than a show of concern for Cyrus's tomb.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Regardless, Alexander the Great ordered Aristobulus to improve the tomb's condition and restore its interior, showing respect for Cyrus.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] From there he headed to Ecbatana, where Darius III had sought refuge.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men murder Darius III and then declared himself Darius' successor, as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia leaving Darius' body in the road to delay Alexander, who brought it to Persepolis for an honourable funeral.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bessus would then create a coalition of his forces, to create an army to defend against Alexander.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander generally kept the original Achaemenid administrative structure, leading some scholars to dub him as "the last of the Achaemenids".
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death in 323 BC, his empire was divided among his generals, the Diadochi, resulting in a number of smaller states.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The largest of these, which held sway over the Iranian plateau, was the Seleucid Empire, ruled by Alexander's general Seleucus I Nicator.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Native Iranian rule would be restored by the Parthians of northeastern Iran over the course of the 2nd century BC through the Parthian Empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Several later Persian rulers, forming the *Frataraka* dynasty, are known to have acted as representatives of the Seleucids in the region of Fārs.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] They ruled from the end of the 3rd century BC to the beginning of the 2nd century BC, and Vahbarz or Vādfradād I obtained independence c.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] 150 BC, when Seleucid power waned in the areas of southwestern Persia and the Persian Gulf region.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] During an apparent transitional period, corresponding to the reigns of Vādfradād II and another uncertain king, no titles of authority appeared on the reverse of their coins.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The earlier title *prtrk' zy alhaya* (Frataraka) had disappeared.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Dārēv I (Darios I) however, the new title of *mlk*, or king, appeared, sometimes with the mention of *prs* (Persis), suggesting that the kings of Persis had become independent rulers.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the Parthian Arsacid king Mithridates I (c.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] 171–138 BC) took control of Persis, he left the Persian dynasts in office, known as the Kings of Persis, and they were allowed to continue minting coins with the title of *mlk* ("King").
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid line would also be carried on through the Kingdom of Pontus, based in the Pontus region of northern Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Pontic Kingdom, a state of Persian origin, may even have been directly related to Darius I and the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was founded by Mithridates I in 281 BC and lasted until its conquest by the Roman Republic in 63 BC.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The kingdom grew to its largest extent under Mithridates VI the Great, who conquered Colchis, Cappadocia, Bithynia, the Greek colonies of the Tauric Chersonesos and for a brief time the Roman province of Asia.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Thus, this Persian dynasty managed to survive and prosper in the Hellenistic world while the main Persian Empire had fallen.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Despite Greek influence on the Kingdom of Pontus, Pontics continued to maintain their Achaemenid lineage.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both the later dynasties of the Parthians and Sasanians would on occasion claim Achaemenid descent.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Recently there has been some corroboration for the Parthian claim to Achaemenid ancestry via the possibility of an inherited disease (neurofibromatosis) demonstrated by the physical descriptions of rulers and from the evidence of familial disease on ancient coinage.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great founded the empire as a multi-state empire, governed from four capital cities: Pasargadae, Babylon, Susa and Ecbatana.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids allowed a certain amount of regional autonomy in the form of the satrapy system.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] A satrapy was an administrative unit, usually organized on a geographical basis.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] A 'satrap' (governor) was the governor who administered the region, a 'general' supervised military recruitment and ensured order, and a 'state secretary' kept the official records.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The general and the state secretary reported directly to the satrap as well as the central government.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] At differing times, there were between 20 and 30 satrapies.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great created an organized army including the Immortals unit, consisting of 10,000 highly trained soldiers Cyrus also formed an innovative postal system throughout the empire, based on several relay stations called Chapar Khaneh.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persepolis Administrative Archives provide many insights into the Achaemenid government system.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Found at Persepolis in the 1930s, they are mostly in Elamite; the remains of more than 10,000 of these cuneiform documents have been uncovered.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Aramaic is represented by about 1,000 or more original records.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Only one tablet in Old Persian has been identified so far.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, many seals and seal impressions are found in these Persepolis archives.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] These documents represent administrative activity and flow of data in Persepolis over more than fifty consecutive years (509–457 BC).
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian daric was the first gold coin which, along with a similar silver coin, the siglos, introduced the bimetallic monetary standard of the Achaemenids, which has continued until today.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was accomplished by Darius I, who reinforced the empire and expanded Persepolis as a ceremonial capital; he revolutionized the economy by placing it on the silver and gold coinage.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius also introduced a regulated and sustainable tax system that was precisely tailored to each satrapy, based on their supposed productivity and their economic potential.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] For instance, Babylon was assessed for the highest amount and for a startling mixture of commodities – 1,000 silver talents, four months' supply of food for the army.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] India was clearly already fabled for its gold; Egypt was known for the wealth of its crops; it was to be the granary of the Persian Empire (as later of Rome's) and was required to provide 120,000 measures of grain in addition to 700 talents of silver.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was exclusively a tax levied on subject peoples.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] There is evidence that conquered and rebellious enemies could be sold into slavery.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alongside its other innovations in administration and taxation, the Achaemenids may have been the first government in the ancient Near East to register private slave sales and tax them using an early form of sales tax.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Other accomplishments of Darius' reign included the codification of the *dāta* (a universal legal system which would become the basis of later Iranian law), and the construction of a new capital at Persepolis.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under the Achaemenids, trade was extensive and there was an efficient infrastructure that facilitated the exchange of commodities in the far reaches of the empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tariffs on trade, along with agriculture and tribute, were major sources of revenue for the empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The satrapies were linked by a 2,500-kilometer highway, the most impressive stretch being the Royal Road from Susa to Sardis, built under the command of Darius I.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] It connected the Iranian Plateau to Central Asia and the Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] It featured stations and caravanserais at specific intervals.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] The relays of mounted couriers (the angarium) could reach the remotest of areas in fifteen days.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus observes that "there is nothing in the world that travels faster than these Persian couriers.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Alexander's conquests, this highway allowed for the spread of cultural syncretic fusions like Greco-Buddhism into Central Asia and China, as well as empires like the Kushan, Indo-Greek and Parthian to profit from trade between East and West.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p01] This route was greatly rehabilitated and formalized during the Abbasid Caliphate, during which it developed into a major component of the famed Silk Road.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite its humble origins in Persis, the empire reached an enormous size under the leadership of Cyrus the Great.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus created a multi-state empire where he allowed regional rulers, satraps, to rule as his proxy over a certain designated area of his empire called a satrapy.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The basic rule of governance was based upon loyalty and obedience of each satrapy to the central power, or the king, and compliance with tax laws.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus managed to create a strong land army, using it to advance in his campaigns in Babylonia, Lydia, and Asia Minor, which after his death was used by his son Cambyses II, in Egypt against Psamtik III.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus would die battling a local Iranian insurgency in the empire, before he could have a chance to develop a naval force.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] That task would fall to Darius I, who would officially give Persians their own royal navy to allow them to engage their enemies on multiple seas of this vast empire, from the Black Sea and the Aegean Sea, to the Persian Gulf, Ionian Sea and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid infantry consisted of three groups: the Immortals, the Sparabara, and the Takabara, though in the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, a fourth group, the Cardaces, were introduced.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Immortals were described by Herodotus as being heavy infantry, led by Hydarnes II, that were kept constantly at a strength of exactly 10,000 men.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] He claimed that the unit's name stemmed from the custom that every killed, seriously wounded, or sick member was immediately replaced with a new one, maintaining the numbers and cohesion of the unit.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] They had wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, and bow and arrows.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Underneath their robes they wore scale armour coats.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The spear counterbalances of the common soldiery were of silver; to differentiate commanding ranks, the officers' spear butt-spikes were golden.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Surviving Achaemenid colored glazed bricks and carved reliefs represent the Immortals as wearing elaborate robes, hoop earrings and gold jewellery, though these garments and accessories were most likely worn only for ceremonial occasions.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were usually the first to engage in hand-to-hand combat with the enemy.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although not much is known about them today, it is believed that they were the backbone of the Persian army who formed a shield wall and used their two-metre-long spears to protect more vulnerable troops such as archers from the enemy.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were taken from the full members of Persian society, were trained from childhood to be soldiers and when not called out to fight on campaigns in distant lands they practised hunting on the vast plains of Persia.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, when all was quiet and the *Pax Persica* held true, the Sparabara returned to normal life farming the land and grazing their herds.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Because of this, they lacked true professional quality on the battlefield, yet they were well trained and courageous to the point of holding the line in most situations long enough for a counter-attack.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] They were armoured with quilted linen and carried large rectangular wicker shields as a form of light maneuverable defence.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] This, however, left them at a severe disadvantage against heavily armoured opponents such as the hoplite, and their two-metre-long spear was not able to give the Sparabara ample range to plausibly engage a trained phalanx.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The wicker shields were able to effectively stop arrows but not strong enough to protect the soldier from spears.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, the Sparabara could deal with most other infantry, including trained units from the East.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenids relied heavily on archery.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Major contributing nations were the Scythians, Medes, Persians, and the Elamites.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The composite bow was used by the Persians and Medes, who adopted it from the Scythians and transmitted it to other nations, including the Greeks.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid armies typically used socketed, three-bladed (also known as trilobate or Scythian) arrowheads.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] These arrowheads were cast from leaded tin-bronze, which made them amenable to mass-production unlike the wrought iron arrowheads of the period that had to be individually forged.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were a rare unit who were a tough type of peltasts.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] They tended to fight with their own native weapons which would have included a crescent-shaped light wickerwork shield and axes as well as light linen cloth and leather.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were recruited from territories that incorporated modern Iran.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian cavalry was crucial for conquering nations and maintained its importance in the Achaemenid army to the last days of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The cavalry was separated into four groups.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers, horse cavalry, the camel cavalry, and the war elephants.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, the chariot archer had become merely a ceremonial part of the Persian army, yet in the early years of the Empire, their use was widespread.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers were armed with lances, bows, arrows, swords, and scale armour.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses were also suited with scale armour similar to scale armour of the Sassanian cataphracts.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariots would contain imperial symbols and decorations.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses used by the Achaemenids for cavalry were often suited with scale armour, like most cavalry units.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The riders often had the same armour as Infantry units, wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, bow and arrow, and scale armour coats.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was different, because the camels and sometimes the riders, were provided little protection against enemies, yet when they were offered protection, they would have lances, swords, bow, arrow, and scale armour.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was first introduced into the Persian army by Cyrus the Great, at the Battle of Thymbra.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The elephant was most likely introduced into the Persian army by Darius I after his conquest of the Indus Valley.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Elephants may have been used in Greek campaigns by Darius and Xerxes I, but Greek accounts only mention 15 of them being used at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Since its foundation by Cyrus, the Persian empire had been primarily a land empire with a strong army but void of any actual naval forces.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] By the 5th century BC, this was to change, as the empire came across Greek and Egyptian forces, each with their own maritime traditions and capabilities.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I was the first Achaemenid king to invest in a Persian fleet.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even by then no true "imperial navy" had existed either in Greece or Egypt.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persia would become the first empire, under Darius, to inaugurate and deploy the first regular imperial navy.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite this achievement, the personnel for the imperial navy would not come from Iran, but were often Phoenicians (mostly from Sidon), Egyptians and Greeks chosen by Darius the Great to operate the empire's combat vessels.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] At first the ships were built in Sidon by the Phoenicians; the first Achaemenid ships measured about 40 meters in length and 6 meters in width, able to transport up to 300 Persian troops at any one trip.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Soon, other states of the empire were constructing their own ships, each incorporating slight local preferences.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships eventually found their way to the Persian Gulf and Persian naval forces laid the foundation for a strong Persian maritime presence there.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persians also had ships often of a capacity 100 to 200 troops patrolling the empire's various rivers including the Karun, Tigris and Nile in the west, as well as the Indus.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid navy established bases located along the Karun, and in Bahrain, Oman, and Yemen.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian fleet was not only used for peace-keeping purposes along the Karun but also opened the door to trade with India via the Persian Gulf.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius's navy was in many ways a world power at the time, but it would be Artaxerxes II who in the summer of 397 BC would build a formidable navy, as part of a rearmament which would lead to his decisive victory at Knidos in 394 BC, re-establishing Achaemenid power in Ionia.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II would also use his navy to later on quell a rebellion in Egypt.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The construction material of choice was wood, but some armoured Achaemenid ships had metallic blades on the front, often meant to slice enemy ships using the ship's momentum.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Naval ships were also equipped with hooks on the side to grab enemy ships, or to negotiate their position.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships were propelled by sails or manpower.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships the Persians created were unique.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] As far as maritime engagement, the ships were equipped with two mangonels that would launch projectiles such as stones, or flammable substances.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Xenophon describes his eyewitness account of a massive military bridge created by joining 37 Persian ships across the Tigris.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persians used each boat's buoyancy to support a connected bridge above which supply could be transferred.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus also gives many accounts of the Persians using ships to build bridges.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I, in an attempt to subdue the Scythian horsemen north of the Black Sea, crossed over at the Bosphorus, using an enormous bridge made by connecting Achaemenid boats, then marched up to the Danube, crossing it by means of a second boat bridge.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The bridge over the Bosphorus essentially connected the nearest tip of Asia to Europe, encompassing at least some 1000 meters of open water if not more.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, a similar boat bridge would be constructed by Xerxes I, in his invasion of Greece.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians failed to capture the Greek city-states completely, the tradition of maritime involvement was carried down by the Persian kings, most notably Artaxerxes II.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, when Alexander invaded Persia and during his advancement into India, he took a page from the Persian art of war, by having Hephaestion and Perdiccas construct a similar boat-bridge at the Indus river in India in the spring of 327 BC.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] They all had the same trilingual inscription (DPh inscription).
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Cyrus II and Darius I, and as long as the seat of government was still at Susa in Elam, the language of the chancellery was Elamite.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] This is primarily attested in the Persepolis fortification and treasury tablets that reveal details of the day-to-day functioning of the empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the grand rock-face inscriptions of the kings, the Elamite texts are always accompanied by Akkadian (Babylonian dialect) and Old Persian inscriptions, and it appears that in these cases that the Elamite texts are translations of the Old Persian ones.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] It is then likely that although Elamite was used by the capital government in Susa, it was not a standardized language of government everywhere in the empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The use of Elamite is not attested after 458 BC.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Following the conquest of Mesopotamia, the Aramaic language (as used in that territory) was adopted as a "vehicle for written communication between the different regions of the vast empire with its different peoples and languages.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] In 1955, Richard Frye questioned the classification of Imperial Aramaic as an official language, noting that no surviving edict expressly and unambiguously accorded that status to any particular language.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Frye reclassifies Imperial Aramaic as the *lingua franca* of the Achaemenid empire, suggesting that the use of Aramaic language in Achaemenid empire was more widespread than generally thought.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many centuries after the fall of the empire, Aramaic script and—as ideograms—Aramaic vocabulary would survive as the essential characteristics of the Pahlavi writing system.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although Old Persian also appears on some seals and art objects, that language is attested primarily in the Achaemenid inscriptions of Western Iran, suggesting then that Old Persian was the common language of that region.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] When the occasion demanded, Achaemenid administrative correspondence was conducted in Greek, making it a widely used bureaucratic language.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even though the Achaemenids had extensive contacts with the Greeks and vice versa, and had conquered many of the Greek-speaking areas both in Europe and Asia Minor during different periods of the empire, the native Old Iranian sources provide no indication of Greek linguistic influence.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, there is plenty of evidence (in addition to the accounts of Herodotus) that Greeks, apart from being deployed and employed in the core regions of the empire, also evidently lived and worked in the heartland of the Achaemenid Empire, namely Iran.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, Greeks were part of the various ethnicities that constructed Darius' palace in Susa, apart from the Greek inscriptions found nearby there, and one short Persepolis tablet written in Greek.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus mentions that the Persians were invited to great birthday feasts (Herodotus, *Histories* 8), which would be followed by many desserts, a treat which they reproached the Greeks for omitting from their meals.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] He also observed that the Persians drank wine in large quantities and used it even for counsel, deliberating on important affairs when drunk, and deciding the next day, when sober, whether to act on the decision or set it aside.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Religious toleration has been described as a "remarkable feature" of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Hebrew Bible reports that Persian king Cyrus the Great released the Jewish people from the Babylonian captivity in 539–530 BC and permitted them to return to their homeland.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus the Great assisted in the restoration of the sacred places of various cities, including to rebuild the Israelites’ Temple in Jerusalem.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] It was during the Achaemenid period that Zoroastrianism reached southwestern Iran, where it came to be accepted by the rulers and through them became a defining element of Persian culture.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The religion was not only accompanied by a formalization of the concepts and divinities of the traditional Iranian pantheon but also introduced several novel ideas, including that of free will.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Mithra was worshipped in the Empire; his temples and symbols were the most widespread, most people bore names related to him and most festivals were dedicated to him.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Artaxerxes I and Darius II, the Greek historian Herodotus wrote: "[the Persians] have no images of the gods, no temples nor altars, and consider the use of them a sign of folly.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] This comes, I think, from their not believing the gods to have the same nature with men, as the Greeks imagine." He claims the Persians offer sacrifice to: "the sun and moon, to the earth, to fire, to water, and to the winds.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] These are the only gods whose worship has come down to them from ancient times.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] At a later period, they began the worship of Urania, which they borrowed from the Arabians and Assyrians.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Babylonian scholar and priest Berosus records—although writing over seventy years after the reign of Artaxerxes II—that the emperor had been the first to make cult statues of divinities and have them placed in temples in many of the major cities of the empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Berosus also substantiates Herodotus when he says the Persians knew of no images of gods until Artaxerxes II erected those images.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] On the means of sacrifice, Herodotus adds "they raise no altar, light no fire, pour no libations." Herodotus also observed that "no prayer or offering can be made without a magus present".
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The position of women in the Achaemenid Empire varied depending on the culture to which they belonged and therefore differed by region.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The hierarchy of royal women at the Persian court was ranked as follows: the king's mother, then the queen, the king's daughters, the king's concubines, and the other women of the royal palace.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king normally married a female member of the royal family or a Persian noblewoman related to a satrap or another important Persian man; it was permitted for members of the royal family to marry relatives, but there is no evidence for marriage between closer family members than half-siblings.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king's concubines were often either slaves, sometimes prisoners of war, or foreign princesses, whom the king did not marry because they were foreigners, and whose children did not have the right to inherit the throne.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Greek sources accuse the king of having hundreds of concubines secluded in a harem.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is no archeological evidence supporting the existence of a harem, or the seclusion of women from contact with men, at the Persian court.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The royal women joined the king at breakfast and dinner and accompanied him on his journeys.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] They may have participated in the royal hunt, as well as during the royal banquets.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus relates how the Persian envoys at the Macedonian court demanded the presence of women during a banquet because it was the custom for women to participate in the banquets in their own country.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The queen may have attended the king's audience, and archeological evidence shows that she gave her own audiences, at least for female supplicants.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal women and noblewomen at court could travel on their own, accompanied by both male and female staff, own and manage their own fortune, land, and business.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Depictions of Persian women show them with long dresses and veils which did not cover their faces or their hair, only flowing down over their neck at the back of the head as an ornament.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic Achaemenid women were given an education in subjects that did not appear compatible with seclusions, such as horsemanship and archery.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women held and managed vast estates and workshops and employed large numbers of servants and professional laborers.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women do not seem to have lived in seclusion from men, since it is known that they appeared in public and traveled with their husbands, participated in hunting and in feasts.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chief wife of a royal or aristocratic man did not live in seclusion, as it is clearly stated that wives customarily accompanied their husbands at dinner banquets.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] They left the banquet when the "women entertainers" came in and the men began "merrymaking".
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] No woman ever ruled the Achaemenid Empire, as monarch or as regent, but some queen's consorts are known to have had influence over the affairs of state, notably Atossa and Parysatis.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is not evidence of any women being employed as an official in the administration or within religious service; however, there are plenty of archeological evidence of women being employed as free labourers in Persepolis, where they worked alongside men.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women could be employed as the leaders of their workforce, known by the title *arraššara pašabena*, which were then given a higher salary than the male workers of their workforce.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Female laborers were given less than men.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Qualified workers within the crafts were given equal pay regardless of their sex.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women are abundant in religious context in the cuneiform sources from late Achaemenid and Hellenistic Babylon.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid architecture included large cities, temples, palaces, and mausolea such as the Tomb of Cyrus the Great.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The quintessential feature of its architecture was its eclectic nature, with elements of Median, Assyrian, and Asiatic Greek all incorporated, yet maintaining a unique Persian identity seen in the finished products.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Its influence pervades the regions ruled by the Achaemenids, from the Mediterranean shores to India, especially with its emphasis on monumental stone-cut design and gardens subdivided by water-courses.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid art includes frieze reliefs, metalwork such as the Oxus Treasure, decoration of palaces, glazed brick masonry, fine craftsmanship (masonry, carpentry, etc.), and gardening.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians drew artists from all corners of their empire, incorporating their styles and techniques, they did not merely produce a combination of styles, but a synthesis of a new, unique Persian style.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] One of the most remarkable examples of both Achaemenid architecture and art is the grand palace of Persepolis, and its detailed workmanship, coupled with its grand scale.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many Achaemenid rulers built tombs for themselves.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The most famous, Naqsh-e Rostam, is an ancient necropolis located about 12 km north-west of Persepolis, with the tombs of four of the kings of the dynasty are carved in this mountain: Darius I, Xerxes I, Artaxerxes I and Darius II.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Other kings constructed their own tombs elsewhere.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II and Artaxerxes III preferred to carve their tombs beside their spring capital Persepolis.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The left tomb belongs to Artaxerxes II and the right tomb belongs to Artaxerxes III, the last Achaemenid king to have a tomb.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The tomb of the founder of the Achaemenid dynasty, Cyrus the Great, was built in Pasargadae (now a world heritage site).
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has been referred to as the first “world empire” as it contained in the words of Persian kings “many people and many languages”.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The diverse groups which made up the empire enjoyed a great deal of legal and cultural autonomy.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has also left a lasting impression on the heritage and cultural identity of Asia and the Middle East, and influenced the development and structure of future empires.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] In fact, the Greeks, and later on the Romans, adopted the best features of the Persian method of governing an empire.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian model of governance was particularly formative in the expansion and maintenance of the Abbasid Caliphate, whose rule is widely considered the period of the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire is noted in Western history as the antagonist of the Greek city-states during the Greco-Persian Wars and for the emancipation of the Jewish exiles in Babylon.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The historical mark of the empire went far beyond its territorial and military influences and included cultural, social, technological and religious influences as well.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, many Athenians adopted Achaemenid customs in their daily lives in a reciprocal cultural exchange, some being employed by or allied to the Persian kings.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The impact of the Edict of Cyrus is mentioned in Judeo-Christian texts, and the empire was instrumental in the spread of Zoroastrianism as far east as China.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] The empire also set the tone for the politics, heritage and history of Iran (also known as Persia).
[src:ancient-philosophy/achaemenid-empire-p02] Hegel in his work *The Philosophy of History* introduces the Persian Empire as the "first empire that passed away" and its people as the "first historical people" in history.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] In Indian religions and society, an ***acharya*** (Sanskrit: आचार्य, IAST: **ācārya**; Pali: *ācariya*) is a religious teacher in Hinduism and Buddhism and a spiritual guide to Hindus and Buddhists.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] The designation has different meanings in Hinduism, Buddhism and secular contexts.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] The Sanskrit phrase *ācāraṁ grahāyati ācāraṁ dadāti iti vā* means *Acharya* (or teacher) is the one who teaches good conduct to one's students.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] The term *'Acharya*' has numerous definitions.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] Hinduism frequently uses the terms "*acharya*" and "*guru*" interchangeably.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] According to the Dharma Shastras, *acharya* is the one who imparts knowledge of the entire Veda to a student and performs upanayana sanskar.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] According to *Nirukta*, an ancillary discipline associated with the Vedas, an acharya is an individual who imparts knowledge to a student, collects wealth from the student, and helps pupils understand behaviour based on moral norms.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] According to *Manusmriti*, the individual who, having initiated a pupil, teaches him the Veda along with the ritualistic and esoteric treatises—him they call, ‘Ācārya,’ ‘Preceptor’—(140).
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] In Buddhism, an ācārya (Pali: *ācariya*) is a senior teacher or master.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] In Theravada it is sometimes used as a title of address for Buddhist monks who have passed ten *vassas*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] In Vajrayana Buddhism, tantric masters are known as vajrācāryas (Tibetan: *dorje lopön;* Chinese: 金剛阿闍梨, pinyin: *jīngāng āshélí*, romanji.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] In Chinese Buddhism, this term is also sometimes alternatively translated as *jingang shangshi* (Chinese: 金剛上師; pinyin: *Jīngāng* *Shàngshī*, lit: "Vajra Superior Master") in the context of certain rituals.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] In Jainism, an *acharya* is the highest leader of a Jain order.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] *Acharya* is one of the Pañca-Parameṣṭhi (five supreme beings) and thus worthy of worship.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] They are the final authority in the monastic order and have the authority to ordain new monks and nuns.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] They also have the authority to consecrate new idols, though they occasionally appoint scholars to carry out this duty.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] An acharya, like any other Jain monk, is expected to wander except for the Chaturmas.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] Bhaṭṭārakas, who head institutions, are technically junior monks, and thus permitted to stay in the same place.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] In Sanskrit institutions, acharya is a post-graduate degree equivalent to Master of Arts in the Anglophone world.
[src:ancient-philosophy/acharya] The equivalent of a PhD is *vidyāvāridhi*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] Advaita schools assert the monistic view that the individual soul and God are one and the same, whereas Dvaita schools give the dualistic argument that the individual soul and God are eternally separate.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] The philosophy of Achintya-bheda-abheda includes elements of both viewpoints.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] The living soul is intrinsically linked with God, and yet at the same time it is not the same as God - the exact nature of this relationship being inconceivable to the human mind.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] The soul is considered to be part and parcel of the God, the same in quality but not in quantity.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] God having all opulence in fullness, the soul, however, having only a partial expression of this divine opulence.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] God in this context is compared to a fire and the souls as sparks coming off of the flame.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] Bhāskara's commentary on the Brahma Sutra is the earliest complete work of Bhedabheda to still exist.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] The Bhedabheda philosophy became the foundation for the traditions of Nimbarka, Vallabha, and Caitanya.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] The theological view of *achintya-bheda-abheda tattva* asserts that God is simultaneously "one with and different from His creation".
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] God's separate existence in His own personal form is not denied, even as creation (or what is termed in Vaishnava theology as the 'cosmic manifestation') is never separate from God.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] God always exercises supreme control over his creation.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] Sometimes this control is directly exercised, but most of the time it is indirect, through his different potencies or energies (Prakrti).
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] Bhaktivedanta Swami Prabhupada summarizes the *achintya-bheda-abheda* philosophy in the following way: "One who knows God knows that the impersonal conception and personal conception are simultaneously present in everything and that there is no contradiction.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] The relationship between the Sun and sunshine analogizes the relationship between God and the *jiva*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] The Sun and sunshine are not different qualitatively, but different quantitively— there is great difference between proximity to a beam of sunshine and proximity to the Sun.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] Similarly, the *jiva* is qualitatively similar to God, but does not share God's qualities to an infinite extent, as would God himself.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] Another conception of difference-in-nondifference is that *jivas* partake in the consciousness and bliss aspect of God, but not the being aspect.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] Thus, *jivas* are ontologically distinct from the absolute body of God.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] The essence of Achintya Bheda Abheda is summarized as ten root principles called dasa mula.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] Krishna is the source of all rasa- flavour, quality, or spiritual rapture/emotions.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] The jivas (individual souls) are all separated parts of the Lord.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] In the bound state (non-liberated), the *jivas* are under the influence of matter due to their tatastha (marginal) nature.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] In the liberated state, the *jivas* are free from the influence of matter.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] The *jivas* and the material world are both different from and identical to the Lord.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] Pure devotion is the only way to attain liberation.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] Pure love of Krishna is the ultimate goal.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] In Advaita Vedanta, the concept of *anirvacaniya* refers to the inexpressible nature of the world; it is neither real nor unreal.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] Thus, *anirvacaniya* is an ontological category.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] In comparison, *acintya* refers to the inconceivability of Bhagavan and his shaktis being different from each other, but at the same time being the same.
[src:ancient-philosophy/achintya-bheda-abheda] This does not negate the reality of both.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] This page lists some links to **ancient philosophy**, namely philosophical thought extending as far as early post-classical history (c.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] Genuine philosophical thought, depending upon original individual insights, arose in many cultures roughly contemporaneously.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] Karl Jaspers termed the intense period of philosophical development beginning around the 7th century BCE and concluding around the 3rd century BCE an Axial Age in human thought.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] The first charter of human rights by Cyrus the Great as understood in the Cyrus cylinder is often seen as a reflection of the questions and thoughts expressed by Zarathustra and developed in Zoroastrian schools of thought of the Achaemenid Era of Iranian history.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] Ideas and tenets of Zoroastrian schools of Early Persian philosophy are part of many works written in Middle Persian and of the extant scriptures of the Zoroastrian religion in Avestan language.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] The **ancient Indian philosophy** is a fusion of two ancient traditions: the Vedic tradition and the śramaṇa tradition.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] Indian philosophy begins with the *Vedas* wherein questions pertaining to laws of nature, the origin of the universe, and the place of man in it are asked.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] In the Vedic view, creation is ascribed to the self-consciousness of the primeval being (*Purusha*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] This leads to the inquiry into *the one being* that underlies the diversity of empirical phenomena and the origin of all things.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] Cosmic order is termed *rta* and causal law by *karma*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] Nature (*prakriti*) is taken to have three qualities (*sattva*, *rajas*, and *tamas*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] Jainism and Buddhism are a continuation of the Sramana school of thought.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] The Sramanas cultivated a pessimistic worldview of the samsara as full of suffering and advocated renunciation and austerities.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] They laid stress on philosophical concepts like Ahimsa, Karma, Jnana, Samsara and Moksa.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] Cārvāka (Sanskrit: चार्वाक) (atheist) philosophy, also known as Lokāyata, it is a system of Hindu philosophy that assumes various forms of philosophical skepticism and religious indifference.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] It is named after its founder, Cārvāka, author of the Bārhaspatya-sūtras.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] In classical times, these inquiries were systematized in six schools of philosophy.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] Chinese philosophy is the dominant philosophical thought in China and other countries within the East Asian cultural sphere that share a common language, including Japan, Korea, and Vietnam.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] The Hundred Schools of Thought were philosophers and schools that flourished from the 6th century to 221 BCE, an era of significant cultural and intellectual expansion in China.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] The thoughts and ideas discussed and refined during this period have profoundly influenced lifestyles and social consciousness up to the present day in East Asian countries.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] The intellectual society of this era was characterized by itinerant scholars, who were often employed by various state rulers as advisers on the methods of government, war, and diplomacy.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] This period ended with the rise of the Qin dynasty and the subsequent purge of dissent.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] The founder of the Qin dynasty, who implemented Legalism as the official philosophy, quashed Mohist and Confucianist schools.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] Legalism remained influential until the emperors of the Han dynasty adopted Daoism and later Confucianism as official doctrine.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] These latter two became the determining forces of Chinese thought until the introduction of Buddhism.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] Confucianism was particularly strong during the Han dynasty, whose greatest thinker was Dong Zhongshu, who integrated Confucianism with the thoughts of the Zhongshu School and the theory of the Five Elements.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] He also was a promoter of the New Text school, which considered Confucius as a divine figure and a spiritual ruler of China, who foresaw and started the evolution of the world towards the Universal Peace.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] In contrast, there was an Old Text school that advocated the use of Confucian works written in ancient language (from this comes the denomination *Old Text*) that were so much more reliable.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] In particular, they refuted the assumption of Confucius as a godlike figure and considered him as the greatest sage, but simply a human and mortal.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] The 3rd and 4th centuries saw the rise of the *Xuanxue* (mysterious learning), also called *Neo-Taoism*.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] The most influential philosophers of this movement were Wang Bi, Xiang Xiu and Guo Xiang.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] The main question of this school was whether Being came before Not-Being (in Chinese, *ming* and *wuming*).
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] A peculiar feature of these Taoist thinkers, like the Seven Sages of the Bamboo Grove, was the concept of *feng liu* (lit. wind and flow), a sort of romantic spirit which encouraged following the natural and instinctive impulse.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] Buddhism arrived in China around the 1st century AD, but it was not until the Northern and Southern, Sui and Tang dynasties that it gained considerable influence and acknowledgement.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] In the beginning, it was considered a sort of Taoist sect, and there was even a theory about Laozi, founder of Taoism, who went to India and taught his philosophy to Buddha.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] Mahayana Buddhism was far more successful in China than its rival Hinayana, and both Indian schools and local Chinese sects arose from the 5th century.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] Two chiefly important monk philosophers were Sengzhao and Daosheng.
[src:ancient-philosophy/ancient-philosophy] But probably the most influential and original of these schools was the Chan sect, which had an even stronger impact in Japan as the Zen sect.
